MEBOL)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2015-16 Campeonato Nacional season}}\n[[Category:2015\u201316 Campeonato Nacional season]]\n[[Category:2015\u201316 in Chilean football]]\n[[Category:2016 in South American football leagues]]\n[[Category:Primera Divisi\u00f3n de Chile seasons]]\n", "name_user": "Cyfal", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling (Wikipedia:Typo Team)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Torneo_Clausura_(Chile)"}
{"title_page": "Magnetic nanoparticles", "text_new": "{{short description|Synthesized magnetic particles of diameter under 100 nanometers with biomedical applications}}\n{{Primary sources|date=August 2016}}\n\n'''Magnetic nanoparticles''' are a class of [[nanoparticle]] that can be manipulated using [[magnetic field]]s. Such particles commonly consist of two components, a magnetic material, often [[iron]], [[nickel]] and [[cobalt]], and a [[chemical]] component that has functionality. While nanoparticles are smaller than 1 micrometer in diameter (typically 1\u2013100 nanometers), the larger [[microbeads]] are 0.5\u2013500 micrometer in diameter. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters that are composed of a number of individual magnetic nanoparticles are known as magnetic nanobeads with a diameter of 50\u2013200 nanometers.<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Tadic|first1=Marin|last2=Kralj|first2=Slavko|last3=Jagodic|first3=Marko|last4=Hanzel|first4=Darko|last5=Makovec|first5=Darko|title=Magnetic properties of novel superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoclusters and their peculiarity under annealing treatment|journal=Applied Surface Science|date=December 2014|volume=322|pages=255\u2013264|doi=10.1016/j.apsusc.2014.09.181|bibcode = 2014ApSS..322..255T }}</ref><ref>Magnetic Nanomaterials, Editors: S H Bossmann, H Wang, Royal Society of Chemistry, Cambridge 2017, https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/ebook/978-1-78801-037-5</ref>Magnetic nanoparticle clusters are a basis for their further magnetic assembly into [[magnetic nanochains]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Makovec|first2=Darko|title=Magnetic Assembly of Superparamagnetic Iron Oxide Nanoparticle Clusters into Nanochains and Nanobundles|journal=ACS Nano|date=27 October 2015|volume=9|issue=10|pages=9700\u20139707|doi=10.1021/acsnano.5b02328|pmid=26394039}}</ref> The magnetic nanoparticles have been the focus of much research recently because they possess attractive properties which could see potential use in [[catalysis]] including [[nanomaterial-based catalyst]]s,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=A.-H. Lu |author2=W. Schmidt |author3=N. Matoussevitch |author4=H. B\u00f6nnemann |author5=B. Spliethoff |author6=B. Tesche |author7=E. Bill |author8=W. Kiefer |author9=F. Sch\u00fcth |date=August 2004 |title=Nanoengineering of a Magnetically Separable Hydrogenation Catalyst |journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition |volume=43 |issue=33 |pages=4303\u20134306 |doi=10.1002/anie.200454222 |pmid=15368378}}</ref> [[biomedicine]] <ref>{{cite journal |author1=A. K. Gupta |author2=M. Gupta |date=June 2005 |title=Synthesis and surface engineering of iron oxide nanoparticles for biomedical applications |journal=Biomaterials  |volume=26 |issue=18 |pages=3995\u20134021 |doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2004.10.012 |pmid=15626447}}</ref> and tissue specific targeting,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ramaswamy|first1=B|last2=Kulkarni|first2=SD|last3=Villar|first3=PS|last4=Smith|first4=RS|last5=Eberly|first5=C|last6=Araneda|first6=RC|last7=Depireux|first7=DA|last8=Shapiro|first8=B|title=Movement of magnetic nanoparticles in brain tissue: mechanisms and safety|journal=Nanomedicine: Nanotechnology, Biology and Medicine|date=24 June 2015|doi=10.1016/j.nano.2015.06.003|pmid=26115639|volume=11|issue=7|pages=1821\u20139|pmc=4586396}}</ref> magnetically tunable colloidal [[photonic crystals]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=He|first1=Le|last2=Wang|first2=Mingsheng|last3=Ge|first3=Jianping|last4=Yin|first4=Yadong|title=Magnetic Assembly Route to Colloidal Responsive Photonic Nanostructures|journal=Accounts of Chemical Research|date=18 September 2012|volume=45|issue=9|pages=1431\u20131440|doi=10.1021/ar200276t|pmid=22578015|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/1274g7zx}}</ref> [[microfluidics]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kavre|first1=Ivna|last2=Kostevc|first2=Gregor|last3=Kralj|first3=Slavko|last4=Vilfan|first4=Andrej|last5=Babi\u010d|first5=Du\u0161an|title=Fabrication of magneto-responsive microgears based on magnetic nanoparticle embedded PDMS|journal=RSC Advances|date=13 August 2014|volume=4|issue=72|pages=38316\u201338322|doi=10.1039/C4RA05602G}}</ref> [[magnetic resonance imaging]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mornet|first1=S.|last2=Vasseur|first2=S.|last3=Grasset|first3=F.|last4=Veverka|first4=P.|last5=Goglio|first5=G.|last6=Demourgues|first6=A.|last7=Portier|first7=J.|last8=Pollert|first8=E.|last9=Duguet|first9=E.|title=Magnetic nanoparticle design for medical applications|journal=Progress in Solid State Chemistry|date=July 2006|volume=34|issue=2\u20134|pages=237\u2013247|doi=10.1016/j.progsolidstchem.2005.11.010}}</ref> [[magnetic particle imaging]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=B. Gleich |author2=J. Weizenecker |journal=  Nature |volume=435|pages= 1214\u20131217 |doi=10.1038/nature03808 |pmid=15988521 |year=2005 |title=Tomographic imaging using the nonlinear response of magnetic particles |issue=7046 |bibcode = 2005Natur.435.1214G }}</ref> [[data storage device|data storage]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hyeon|first1=Taeghwan|title=Chemical synthesis of magnetic nanoparticles|journal=Chemical Communications|date=3 April 2003|issue=8|pages=927\u2013934|doi=10.1039/B207789B|pmid=12744306|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/785c6c1445e1a2d54389fa95954b525f26798cce}}</ref><ref name=\"nanoscienceworks.org\">Natalie A. Frey and Shouheng Sun [https://web.archive.org/web/20111004094259/http://www.nanoscienceworks.org/publications/just-in-print/K10915_chapter3%20(2).pdf Magnetic Nanoparticle for Information Storage Applications]</ref> [[environmental remediation]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Elliott|first1=Daniel W.|last2=Zhang|first2=Wei-xian|title=Field Assessment of Nanoscale Bimetallic Particles for Groundwater Treatment|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|date=December 2001|volume=35|issue=24|pages=4922\u20134926|doi=10.1021/es0108584|pmid=11775172|bibcode = 2001EnST...35.4922E }}</ref> [[nanofluids]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=J. Philip |author2=Shima.P.D. B. Raj |year=2006 |title= Nanofluid with tunable thermal properties |journal= Applied Physics Letters |volume=92 |issue=4 | pages=043108| doi=10.1063/1.2838304|bibcode = 2008ApPhL..92d3108P }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1088/1361-6463/aa4f92|title = Self pumping magnetic cooling|journal = Journal of Physics D: Applied Physics|volume = 50|issue = 3|pages = 03LT03|year = 2017|last1 = Chaudhary|first1 = V.|last2 = Wang|first2 = Z.|last3 = Ray|first3 = A.|last4 = Sridhar|first4 = I.|last5 = Ramanujan|first5 = R. V.|bibcode = 2017JPhD...50cLT03C}}</ref>, optical filters,<ref>{{cite journal |author1= J.Philip |author2= T.J.Kumar |author3= P.Kalyanasundaram |author4= B.Raj|year=2003 |title= Tunable Optical Filter |journal= Measurement Science and Technology |volume=14 |issue=8 | pages=1289\u20131294 |doi=10.1088/0957-0233/14/8/314|bibcode = 2003MeScT..14.1289P }}</ref>  defect sensor <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mahendran | first1 = V. | title = Nanofluid based opticalsensor for rapid visual inspection of defects in ferromagnetic materials | url = | journal = Appl. Phys. Lett. | volume = 100 | issue = 7| page = 073104 | doi = 10.1063/1.3684969 |bibcode = 2012ApPhL.100g3104M | year = 2012 }}</ref>, magnetic cooling<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chaudhary |first1=V. |last2=Ramanujan |first2=R. V. |title=Magnetocaloric Properties of Fe-Ni-Cr Nanoparticles for Active Cooling |journal=Scientific Reports |date=11 October 2016 |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=35156 |doi=10.1038/srep35156 |pmid=27725754 |pmc=5057077 |bibcode=2016NatSR...635156C }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chaudhary |first1=V. |last2=Chen |first2=X. |last3=Ramanujan |first3=R.V. |title=Iron and manganese based magnetocaloric materials for near room temperature thermal management |journal=Progress in Materials Science |date=February 2019 |volume=100 |pages=64\u201398 |doi=10.1016/j.pmatsci.2018.09.005 }}</ref> and cation sensors.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Philip | first1 = V. Mahendran | last2 = Felicia | first2 = Leona J. | year = 2013 | title = A Simple, In-Expensive and Ultrasensitive Magnetic Nanofluid Based Sensor for Detection of Cations, Ethanol and Ammonia | url = | journal = Journal of Nanofluids| volume = 2 | issue = 2| pages = 112\u2013119 | doi = 10.1166/jon.2013.1050 }}</ref>\n\n== Properties ==\nThe physical and chemical properties of magnetic nanoparticles largely depend on the synthesis method and chemical structure. In most cases, the particles range from 1 to 100&nbsp;nm in size and may display [[superparamagnetism]].<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\">{{cite journal |author1=A.-H. Lu |author2=E. L. Salabas |author3=F. Sch\u00fcth |journal =Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.|year= 2007|volume= 46|pages=1222\u20131244 |doi=10.1002/anie.200602866 |pmid=17278160 |title=Magnetic Nanoparticles: Synthesis, Protection, Functionalization, and Application |issue=8}}</ref>\n\n== Types of magnetic nanoparticles ==\n\n=== Oxides: ferrites ===\n[[Ferrite (magnet)|Ferrite]] nanoparticles or [[iron oxide nanoparticles]] ([[iron oxides]] in crystal structure of [[maghemite]] or [[magnetite]]) are the most explored magnetic nanoparticles up to date. Once the ferrite particles become smaller than 128&nbsp;nm<ref name=\"Angew.review\">{{cite journal|last=An-Hui Lu|author2=E. L. Salabas |author3=Ferdi Sch\u00fcth |journal=Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.|year=2007|volume=46|pages=1222\u20131244|doi= 10.1002/anie.200602866|pmid=17278160 |title=Magnetic Nanoparticles: Synthesis, Protection, Functionalization, and Application|first1=An-Hui|issue=8}}</ref> they become [[superparamagnetic]] which prevents self agglomeration since they exhibit their magnetic behavior only when an external magnetic field is applied. The magnetic moment of ferrite nanoparticles can be greatly increased by controlled clustering of a number of individual superparamagnetic nanoparticles into superparamagnetic nanoparticle clusters, namely [[magnetic nanobeads]].<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\" /> With the external magnetic field switched off, the [[remanence]] falls back to zero. Just like non-magnetic oxide nanoparticles, the surface of ferrite nanoparticles is often modified by [[surfactant]]s, [[silica]],<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\" /> [[silicones]] or [[phosphoric acid]] derivatives to increase their stability in solution.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kim, DK|journal=Chemistry of Materials|year=2003|volume=15|issue=8|pages=1617\u20131627|doi=10.1021/cm001253u|author2=Mikhaylova, M|last3=Zhang|first3=Y|display-authors=2|title=Anchoring of Phosphonate and Phosphinate Coupling Molecules on Titania Particles|first1=G.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maghemite silica nanoparticle cluster.jpg|right|thumbnail|400px|alt=Maghemite nanoparticle cluster with silica shell.|[[Transmission electron microscopy|TEM]] image of a maghemite magnetic nanoparticle cluster with silica shell.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>http://nanos-sci.com/technology.html Properties and use of magnetic nanoparticle clusters (magnetic nanobeads)</ref>]]\n\n=== Ferrites with a shell===\nThe surface of a maghemite or magnetite magnetic nanoparticle is relatively inert and does not usually allow strong covalent bonds with functionalization molecules. However, the reactivity of the magnetic nanoparticles can be improved by coating a layer of [[silica]] onto their surface.<ref name=\"Kralj et al 2010 Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Makovec|first2=Darko|last3=\u010campelj|first3=Stanislav|last4=Drofenik|first4=Miha|title=Producing ultra-thin silica coatings on iron-oxide nanoparticles to improve their surface reactivity|journal=Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials|date=July 2010|volume=322|issue=13|pages=1847\u20131853|doi=10.1016/j.jmmm.2009.12.038|bibcode = 2010JMMM..322.1847K }}</ref> The [[silica]] shell can be easily modified with various surface functional groups via covalent bonds between organo-silane molecules and silica shell.<ref name=\"Kralj et al 2010 Journal of Nanoparticle Research\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Drofenik|first2=Miha|last3=Makovec|first3=Darko|title=Controlled surface functionalization of silica-coated magnetic nanoparticles with terminal amino and carboxyl groups|journal=Journal of Nanoparticle Research|date=16 December 2010|volume=13|issue=7|pages=2829\u20132841|doi=10.1007/s11051-010-0171-4|bibcode=2011JNR....13.2829K}}</ref> In addition, some [[fluorescent dye]] molecules can be covalently bonded to the functionalized [[silica]] shell.<ref name=\"Kralj 2012 Journal of Nanoparticle Research\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Rojnik|first2=Matija|last3=Romih|first3=Rok|last4=Jagodi\u010d|first4=Marko|last5=Kos|first5=Janko|last6=Makovec|first6=Darko|title=Effect of surface charge on the cellular uptake of fluorescent magnetic nanoparticles|journal=Journal of Nanoparticle Research|date=7 September 2012|volume=14|issue=10|pages=1151|doi=10.1007/s11051-012-1151-7|bibcode=2012JNR....14.1151K}}</ref>\n\nFerrite nanoparticle clusters with narrow size distribution consisting of superparamagnetic oxide nanoparticles (~ 80 maghemite superparamagnetic nanoparticles per bead) coated with a silica shell have several advantages over metallic nanoparticles:<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\"/>\n\n*Higher chemical stability (crucial for biomedical applications)\n*Narrow size distribution (crucial for biomedical applications)\n*Higher colloidal stability since they do not magnetically agglomerate\n*Magnetic moment can be tuned with the nanoparticle cluster size\n*Retained superparamagnetic properties (independent of the nanoparticle cluster size)\n*Silica surface enables straightforward covalent functionalization\n\n=== Metallic ===\nMetallic nanoparticles may be beneficial for some technical applications due to their higher magnetic moment whereas oxides ([[maghemite]], [[magnetite]]) would be beneficial for biomedical applications. This also implies that for the same moment, metallic nanoparticles can be made smaller than their oxide counterparts. On the other hand, metallic nanoparticles have the great disadvantage of being [[pyrophoric]] and reactive to [[oxidizing agents]] to various degrees. This makes their handling difficult and enables unwanted side reactions which makes them less appropriate for biomedical applications. Colloid formation for metallic particles is also much more challenging.\n\n[[File:Cobalt-graphene-nanoparticle.tif|frame|upright|alt=Cobalt nanoparticle with graphene shell.|Cobalt nanoparticle with graphene shell (note: The individual [[graphene]] layers are visible)<ref name=\"R.N. Grass 2007 4909\u201312\">{{cite journal|last=R.N. Grass |author2=E.K. Athanassiou |author3=W.J. Stark|journal=Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.|year=2007|volume=46|pages=4909\u201312|doi=10.1002/anie.200700613|title=Covalently Functionalized Cobalt Nanoparticles as a Platform for Magnetic Separations in Organic Synthesis|first1=Robert N.|issue=26|pmid=17516598}}</ref>]]\n\n=== Metallic with a shell ===\nThe metallic core of magnetic nanoparticles may be passivated by gentle oxidation, surfactants, polymers and precious metals.<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/> In an oxygen environment, Co nanoparticles form an anti-ferromagnetic CoO layer on the surface of the Co nanoparticle. Recently, work has explored the synthesis and exchange bias effect in these Co core CoO shell nanoparticles with a gold outer shell.<ref name=\"Johnsonj.mater.chem.2010\">\n{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Stephanie H. |author2=C.L. Johnson |author3=S.J. May |author4=S. Hirsch |author5=M.W. Cole |author6=J.E. Spanier|title=Co@CoO@Au core-multi-shell nanocrystals|journal=Journal of Materials Chemistry|year=2010|volume=20|pages=439\u2013443|doi=10.1039/b919610b|issue=3}}</ref>\nNanoparticles with a magnetic core consisting either of elementary [[Iron]] or [[Cobalt]] with a nonreactive shell made of [[graphene]] have been synthesized recently.<ref name=\"j.mater.chem.2006\">{{cite journal|last=R. N. Grass|author2=W. J. Stark|journal=J. Mater. Chem.|year=2006|issue=19|page=1825|doi=10.1039/B601013J|title=Gas phase synthesis of fcc-cobalt nanoparticles|first1=Robert N.|volume=16|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/663a70017aa8db59caaf080f774f74ce7e75b01f}}</ref> The advantages compared to ferrite or elemental nanoparticles are:\n* Higher [[magnetization]]\n* Higher stability in [[acidic]] and [[Base (chemistry)|basic]] solution as well as [[organic solvents]]\n* Chemistry<ref name=\"R.N. Grass 2007 4909\u201312\"/>  on the graphene surface via methods already known for [[carbon nanotubes]]\n\n== Synthesis ==\n\nSeveral methods exist for preparing magnetic [[nanoparticle]].\n\n=== Co-precipitation ===\n{{main|Co-precipitation}}\nCo-precipitation is a facile and convenient way to synthesize iron oxides (either Fe<sub>3</sub>O<sub>4</sub> or \u03b3-Fe<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>) from aqueous Fe<sup>2+</sup>/Fe<sup>3+</sup> salt solutions by the addition of a base under inert\natmosphere at room temperature or at elevated temperature. The size, shape, and composition of the magnetic nanoparticles very much depends on the type of salts used (e.g.chlorides, sulfates, nitrates), the Fe<sup>2+</sup>/Fe<sup>3+</sup> ratio, the reaction [[temperature]], the [[pH]] value and [[ionic strength]] of the media,<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/> and the mixing rate with the base solution used to provoke the precipitation.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fang | first1 = Mei | last2 = Str\u00f6m | first2 = Valter | last3 = Olsson | first3 = Richard T. | last4 = Belova | first4 = Lyubov | last5 = Rao | first5 = K. V. | title = Rapid mixing: A route to synthesize magnetite nanoparticles with high moment| url = | journal = Appl. Phys. Lett. | volume = 99 | issue = 22| page = 222501 | doi=10.1063/1.3662965|bibcode = 2011ApPhL..99v2501F | year = 2011 }}</ref> The co-precipitation approach has been used extensively to produce ferrite nanoparticles of controlled sizes and magnetic properties.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= G.Gnanaprakash |author2=S.Ayyappan |author3=T.Jayakumar |author4=John Philip |author5=Baldev Raj  |year=2006 |title= A simple method to produce magnetic nanoparticles with enhanced alpha to gamma-Fe2O3 phase transition temperature |journal= Nanotechnology |volume=17 |issue=23 | pages=5851\u20135857|bibcode = 2006Nanot..17.5851G |doi = 10.1088/0957-4484/17/23/023 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=G. Gnanaprakash |author2=John Philip |author3=T. Jayakumar |author4=Baldev Raj |year=2007 |title= Effect of Digestion Time and Alkali Addition Rate on the Physical Properties of Magnetite Nanoparticles |journal= J. Phys. Chem. B   |volume=111 |issue=28 | pages=7978\u20137986 |doi=10.1021/jp071299b|pmid=17580856 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=S.Ayyappan, John Philip  |author2=Baldev Raj  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2009 |title= Solvent polarity effect on physical properties of CoFe2O3 nanoparticles |journal= J. Phys. Chem. C   |volume=113 |issue=2  | pages=590\u2013596 |doi=10.1021/jp8083875}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=S. Ayyappan |author2=S. Mahadevan |author3=P. Chandramohan |author4=M. P.Srinivasan |author5=John Philip |author6=Baldev Raj |year=2010 |title= Influence of Co2 Ion Concentration on the Size, Magnetic Properties, and Purity of CoFe2O4 Spinel Ferrite Nanoparticles |journal= J. Phys. Chem. C   |volume=114 |issue=14 | pages=6334\u20136341 |doi=10.1021/jp911966p}}</ref> A variety of experimental arrangements have been reported to facilitate continuous and large\u2013scale co\u2013precipitation of magnetic particles by rapid mixing.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fun Chin | first1 = Suk | last2 = Iyer | first2 = K. Swaminathan | last3 = Raston | first3 = Colin L. | authorlink3 = Colin Raston | last4 = Saunders | first4 = Martin | year = 2008 | title = Size Selective Synthesis of Superparamagnetic Nanoparticles in Thin Fluids under Continuous Flow Conditions| url = http://ir.unimas.my/9899/1/Size%20Selective%20Synthesis%20of%20Superparamagnetic%20Nanoparticles%20in%20Thin%20Fluids%20under%20Continuous%20Flow%20Conditions%20%28abstract%29.pdf| journal = Adv. Funct. Mater. | volume = 18 | issue = 6| pages = 922\u2013927 | doi=10.1002/adfm.200701101}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Raston |first1=CL |last2=Saunders |first2=M |last3=Smith |first3=N |last4=Woodward |first4=R |title=Synthesis of Magnetic Nanoparticles Using Spinning Disc Processing |journal=TechConnect Briefs |date=7 May 2006 |volume=1 |issue=2006 |pages=343\u2013346 |url=https://briefs.techconnect.org/papers/synthesis-of-magnetic-nanoparticles-using-spinning-disc-processing/ }}</ref> Recently, the growth rate of the magnetic nanoparticles was measured in real-time during the precipitation of magnetite nanoparticles by an integrated AC magnetic susceptometer within the mixing zone of the reactants.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Str\u00f6m |first1=Valter |last2=Olsson |first2=Richard T. |last3=Rao |first3=K. V. |title=Real-time monitoring of the evolution of magnetism during precipitation of superparamagnetic nanoparticles for bioscience applications |journal=Journal of Materials Chemistry |date=2010 |volume=20 |issue=20 |pages=4168 |doi=10.1039/c0jm00043d }}</ref>\n\n=== Thermal decomposition ===\n{{main|Thermal decomposition}}\nMagnetic nanocrystals with smaller size can essentially be synthesized through the thermal decomposition of alkaline organometallic compounds in high-boiling organic solvents containing stabilizing surfactants.<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sharifi|first=Ibrahim|last2=Zamanian|first2=Ali|last3=Behnamghader|first3=Aliasghar|date=2016-08-15|title=Synthesis and characterization of Fe0.6Zn0.4Fe2O4 ferrite magnetic nanoclusters using simple thermal decomposition method|journal=Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials|volume=412|pages=107\u2013113|doi=10.1016/j.jmmm.2016.03.091|issn=0304-8853|bibcode=2016JMMM..412..107S}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Monfared|first=A. H.|last2=Zamanian|first2=A.|last3=Beygzadeh|first3=M.|last4=Sharifi|first4=I.|last5=Mozafari|first5=M.|date=2017-02-05|title=A rapid and efficient thermal decomposition approach for the synthesis of manganese-zinc/oleylamine core/shell ferrite nanoparticles|journal=Journal of Alloys and Compounds|volume=693|pages=1090\u20131095|doi=10.1016/j.jallcom.2016.09.253|issn=0925-8388}}</ref>\n\n=== Microemulsion ===\n{{main|Microemulsion}}\nUsing the microemulsion technique, metallic cobalt, cobalt/platinum alloys, and gold-coated cobalt/platinum nanoparticles have been synthesized in reverse [[micelles]] of cetyltrimethlyammonium bromide, using 1-butanol as the cosurfactant and octane as the oil phase.,<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/><ref>{{cite journal |author1= S S.Rana |author2=J. Philip |author3=B.Raj  |year=2010 |title= Micelle based synthesis of Cobalt Ferrite nanoparticles and its characterization using Fourier Transform Infrared Transmission Spectrometry and Thermogravimetry |journal= Materials Chemistry and Physics   |volume=124 | pages=264\u2013269 |doi=10.1016/j.matchemphys.2010.06.029}}</ref>\n\n=== Flame spray synthesis ===\nUsing [[Flame spray|flame spray pyrolysis ]]<ref name=\"j.mater.chem.2006\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=E. K. Athanassiou|author2=R. N. Grass |author3=W. J. Stark |journal=Aerosol. Sci. Tech.|year=2010|volume=44|issue=2|pages=161\u201372|doi=10.1080/02786820903449665|title=Chemical Aerosol Engineering as a Novel Tool for Material Science: From Oxides to Salt and Metal Nanoparticles|first1=Evagelos K.|bibcode=2010AerST..44..161A}}</ref>  and varying the reaction conditions, oxides, metal or carbon coated nanoparticles are produced at a rate of > 30 g/h .\n\n{|\n| [[File:Flame-spray-synthesis.JPG|frame|center|alt=Various flame spray conditions and their impact on the resulting nanoparticles|Various flame spray conditions and their impact on the resulting [[nanoparticles]]]]\n| [[File:Flame-spray-synthesis-2.JPG|frame|center|alt=Operational layout differences between conventional and reducing flame spray synthesis|Operational layout differences between conventional and reducing flame spray synthesis]]\n|}\n\n== Potential applications ==\nA wide variety of potential applications have been envisaged.  Since magnetic nanoparticles are expensive to produce, there is interest in their recycling or for highly specialized applications.\n\nThe potential and versatility of magnetic chemistry arises from the fast and easy separation of the magnetic nanoparticles, eliminating tedious and costly [[separation processes]] usually applied in chemistry. Furthermore, the magnetic nanoparticles can be guided via a magnetic field to the desired location which could, for example, enable pinpoint precision in fighting cancer.\n\n=== Medical diagnostics and treatments ===\n\nMagnetic nanoparticles have been examined for use in an [[experimental cancer treatment]] called [[magnetic hyperthermia]] <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rabias | first1 = I. | display-authors = etal   | title = Rapid magnetic heating treatment by highly charged maghemite nanoparticles on Wistar rats exocranial glioma tumors at microliter volume| url = | journal = Biomicrofluidics | volume = 4 | issue = 2| page = 024111 | doi = 10.1063/1.3449089 | pmid = 20697578 | pmc = 2917883| year = 2010 }}</ref> in which an alternating magnetic field (AMF) is used to heat the nanoparticles. To achieve sufficient magnetic nanoparticle heating, the AMF typically has a frequency between 100\u2013500&nbsp;kHz, although significant research has been done at lower frequencies as well as frequencies as high as 10&nbsp;MHz, with the amplitude of the field usually between 8-16kAm<sup>\u22121</sup>.<ref name = \"Kumar\">{{cite journal | pmid = 21447363 | doi=10.1016/j.addr.2011.03.008 | pmc=3138885 | volume=63 | issue=9 | title=Magnetic nanomaterials for hyperthermia-based therapy and controlled drug delivery | year=2011 | journal=Adv. Drug Deliv. Rev. | pages=789\u2013808 | last1 = Kumar | first1 = CS | last2 = Mohammad | first2 = F}}</ref>\n\nAffinity ligands such as epidermal growth factor ([[Epidermal growth factor|EGF]]), [[folic acid]], [[aptamer]]s, [[lectin]]s etc. can be attached to the magnetic nanoparticle surface with the use of various chemistries. This enables targeting of magnetic nanoparticles to specific tissues or cells.<ref name=\"Kralj et al 2013 EGF\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Rojnik|first2=Matija|last3=Kos|first3=Janko|last4=Makovec|first4=Darko|title=Targeting EGFR-overexpressed A431 cells with EGF-labeled silica-coated magnetic nanoparticles|journal=Journal of Nanoparticle Research|date=26 April 2013|volume=15|issue=5|pages=1666|doi=10.1007/s11051-013-1666-6|bibcode=2013JNR....15.1666K}}</ref> This strategy is used in cancer research to target and treat tumors in combination with [[magnetic hyperthermia]] or nanoparticle-delivered [[cancer drug]]s. Despite research efforts, however, the accumulation of nanoparticles inside of cancer tumors of all types is sub-optimal, even with affinity ligands. Willhelm et al. conducted a broad analysis of nanoparticle delivery to tumors and concluded that the median amount of injected dose reaching a solid tumor is only 0.7%.<ref name = \"Willhelm 2016\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/natrevmats.2016.14|title=Analysis of nanoparticle delivery to tumours|journal=Nature Reviews Materials|volume=1|issue=5|pages=16014|year=2016|last1=Wilhelm|first1=Stefan|last2=Tavares|first2=Anthony J.|last3=Dai|first3=Qin|last4=Ohta|first4=Seiichi|last5=Audet|first5=Julie|last6=Dvorak|first6=Harold F.|last7=Chan|first7=Warren C. W.|bibcode=2016NatRM...116014W}}</ref> The challenge of accumulating large amounts of nanoparticles inside of tumors is arguably the biggest obstacle facing nanomedicine in general. While direct injection is used in some cases, intravenous injection is most often preferred to obtain a good distribution of particles throughout the tumor. Magnetic nanoparticles have a distinct advantage in that they can accumulate in desired regions via magnetically guided delivery, although this technique still needs further development to achieve optimal delivery to solid tumors.\n\nAnother potential treatment of cancer includes attaching magnetic nanoparticles to free-floating cancer cells, allowing them to be captured and carried out of the body. The treatment has been tested in the laboratory on mice and will be looked at in survival studies.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Scarberry KE, Dickerson EB, McDonald JF, Zhang ZJ |year=2008|title=Magnetic Nanoparticle-Peptide Conjugates for in Vitro and in Vivo Targeting and Extraction of Cancer Cells |journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society |pmid=18611005 |doi=10.1021/ja801969b |volume=130 |pages=10258\u201362 |issue=31 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.newswise.com/articles/view/542665 Using Magnetic Nanoparticles to Combat Cancer] Newswise, Retrieved on July 17, 2008.</ref>\n\nMagnetic nanoparticles can be used for the detection of cancer. Blood can be inserted onto a microfluidic chip with magnetic nanoparticles in it. These magnetic nanoparticles are trapped inside due to an externally applied magnetic field as the blood is free to flow through. The magnetic nanoparticles are coated with antibodies targeting cancer cells or proteins.  The magnetic nanoparticles can be recovered and the attached cancer-associated molecules can be assayed to test for their existence.\n\nMagnetic nanoparticles can be conjugated with carbohydrates and used for detection of bacteria. Iron oxide particles have been used for the detection of Gram negative bacteria like [[Escherichia coli]] and for detection of Gram positive bacteria like [[Streptococcus suis]]<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Parera Pera N |author2=Kouki A. |author3=Finne J. |author4=Pieters R. J. |year=2010  |title=Detection of pathogenic Streptococcus suis bacteria using magnetic glycoparticles |journal= Organic & Biomolecular Chemistry|doi=10.1039/C000819B |pmid=20448902 |volume=8 |pages=2425\u20132429 |issue=10 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f5c71a62e8892e142c8e7768b7b905a3d2e151a9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsc.org/Publishing/Journals/cb/Volume/2010/05/an_attractive_method.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021043001/http://www.rsc.org/Publishing/Journals/cb/Volume/2010/05/an_attractive_method.asp |archivedate=21 October 2012 |title=An attractive method for bacteria detection |date=30 March 2010 |work=Highlights in Chemical Biology |first1=David |last1=Barden }}</ref>\n\n=== Magnetic immunoassay ===\n[[Magnetic immunoassay]]<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html Magnetic immunoassays: A new paradigm in POCT] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080830062331/http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html |date=2008-08-30 }} IVDt, July/August 2008.</ref> (MIA) is a novel type of diagnostic immunoassay utilizing [[magnetic nanobeads]] as labels in lieu of conventional, enzymes, radioisotopes or fluorescent moieties. This assay involves the specific binding of an antibody to its antigen, where a magnetic label is conjugated to one element of the pair. The presence of [[magnetic nanobeads]] is then detected by a magnetic reader (magnetometer) which measures the magnetic field change induced by the beads. The signal measured by the magnetometer is proportional to the analyte (virus, toxin, bacteria, cardiac marker, etc.) quantity in the initial sample.\n\n=== Waste water treatment ===\nThanks to the easy separation by applying a magnetic field and the very large [[surface to volume ratio]], magnetic nanoparticles have a potential for treatment of contaminated water.<ref>{{cite journal|last=F.M. Koehler |author2=M. Rossier |author3=M. Waelle |author4=E.K. Athanassiou |author5=L.K. Limbach |author6=R.N. Grass |author7=D. G\u00fcnther |author8=W.J. Stark|journal=Chem. Commun.|year=2009|volume=32|pages=4862\u20134|doi=10.1039/B909447D|pmid=19652806 |title=Magnetic EDTA: Coupling heavy metal chelators to metal nanomagnets for rapid removal of cadmium, lead and copper from contaminated water|first1=Fabian M.|issue=32|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1b7c55dfcb27958f6eedd5480a8c5c2ebc6e26f4 }}</ref>\nIn this method, attachment of EDTA-like chelators to carbon coated metal nanomagnets results in a magnetic reagent for the rapid removal of heavy metals from solutions or contaminated water by three orders of magnitude to concentrations as low as micrograms per Litre. [[Magnetic nanobeads]] or nanoparticle clusters composed of FDA-approved oxide superparamagnetic nanoparticles (e.g. [[maghemite]], [[magnetite]]) hold much potential for waste water treatment since they express excellent [[biocompatibility]] which concerning the [[environmental impacts]] of the material is an advantage compared to metallic nanoparticles.\n\n=== Supported enzymes and peptides===\nEnzymes, proteins, and other biologically and chemically active substances have been immobilized on magnetic nanoparticles.<ref name=\"biocatalyst\">{{cite journal|last=Huang-Hao Yang |author2=Shu-Qiong Zhang |author3=Xiao-Lan Chen |author4=Zhi-Xia Zhuang |author5=Jin-Gou Xu |author6=Xiao-Ru Wang|journal=Analytical Chemistry|year=2004|volume=76|pages=1316\u20131321|doi=10.1021/ac034920m|title=Magnetite-Containing Spherical Silica Nanoparticles for Biocatalysis and Bioseparations|first1=Huang-Hao|issue=5|pmid=14987087}}</ref>  \nThe immobilization of enzymes on inexpensive, non-toxic and easily-synthesized iron magnetic\nnanoparticles (MNP) has shown great promise due to more stable proteins, better product yield, ease of protein purification and multiple usage as a result of their magnetic susceptibility <ref>Siddiqui KS, Shemsi AM, Guerriero G, Najnin T, Taha, Ertan H, 2017. Biotechnological improvements of cold-adapted enzymes: commercialization via an integrated approach. In: Margesin, Rosa (Ed.), Psychrophiles: From Biodiversity to Biotechnology, Springer-Verlag, pp. 477\u2013512.</ref>.\nThey are of interest as possible supports for [[solid phase synthesis]].<ref name=\"magnetic.peptide\">{{cite journal|last=K.Nor\u00e9n|author2=M. Kempe|journal=International Journal of Peptide Research and Therapeutics|year=2009|volume=15|issue=4|pages=287\u2013292|doi= 10.1007/s10989-009-9190-3|title=Multilayered Magnetic Nanoparticles as a Support in Solid-Phase Peptide Synthesis|first1=Katarina}}</ref>\n\nThis technology is potentially relevant to cellular labelling/cell separation, detoxification of biological fluids, tissue repair, drug delivery, magnetic resonance imaging, hyperthermia and magnetofection.<ref name=\"medicine\">{{cite journal|last=Gupta AK|author2=Gupta M|journal=Biomaterials|year=2005|volume=26|issue=18|pages=3995\u20134021|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2004.10.012|title=Synthesis and surface engineering of iron oxide nanoparticles for biomedical applications|first1=Ajay Kumar|pmid=15626447}}</ref>\n\n'''Random versus site-directed enzyme immobilization'''\n\nEnzymes immobilized on magnetic nanoparticles (MNP) via random multipoint attachment, result in a heterogeneous protein population with reduced activity due to restriction of substrate access to the active site. Methods based on chemical modifications are now available where MNP can be linked to a protein molecule via a single specific amino acid (such as N- or C- termini), thus avoiding reduction in activity due the free access of the substrate to the active site. Moreover, site-directed immobilization also avoids modifying catalytic residues. One such common method involves using Alkyne-Azide Click chemistry as both groups are absent in proteins <ref>Shemsi, AM, Khanday F, Qureshi AH, Khalil A, Guerriero G, *Siddiqui KS (2019). Site-directed chemically-modified magnetic enzymes: fabrication, improvements, biotechnological applications and future prospects. Biotechnol. Adv. 37:357-381</ref>.\n\n===Catalyst support===\nMagnetic nanoparticles are of potential use as a [[catalyst]] or [[catalyst support]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A. Sch\u00e4tz |author2=O. Reiser |author3=W.J. Stark|journal=Chem. Eur. J.|year=2010|volume=16|issue=30|pages=8950\u201367|doi=10.1002/chem.200903462|pmid=20645330 |title=Nanoparticles as Semi-Heterogeneous Catalyst Supports|first1=Alexander}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=F. Panahi |author2=F. Bahrami |author3=A. Khalafi-nezhad|journal=Journal of Iranian Chemical Society|year=2017|volume=14|issue=10|pages=2211\u201320|doi=10.1007/s13738-017-1157-2|title=Magnetic nanoparticles grafted l-carnosine dipeptide: remarkable catalytic activity in water at room temperature}}</ref>\nIn chemistry, a catalyst support is the material, usually a solid with a high surface area, to which a catalyst is affixed. The reactivity of heterogeneous catalysts occurs at the surface atoms. Consequently, great effort is made to maximize the surface area of a catalyst by distributing it over the support. The support may be inert or participate in the catalytic reactions. Typical supports include various kinds of carbon, alumina, and silica. Immobilizing the catalytic center on top of nanoparticles with a large [[surface to volume ratio]] addresses this problem. In the case of magnetic nanoparticles it adds the property of facile a separation<!-- Needs clarification.... -->. An early example involved a rhodium catalysis attached to magnetic nanoparticles .<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tae-Jong Yoon |author2=Woo Lee |author3=Yoon-Seuk Oh |author4=Jin-Kyu Lee|journal=New Journal of Chemistry|year=2003|volume=27|pages=227.229|doi=10.1039/B209391J|title=Magnetic nanoparticles as a catalyst vehicle for simple and easy recycling |first1=Tae-Jong|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Magnetic-chemistry-1.tif|frameless|center|430px|alt=Rhodium catalysis attached to magnetic nanoparticles]]\n\nIn another example, the stable [[Radical (chemistry)|radical]] [[TEMPO]] was attached to the [[graphene]]-coated cobalt nanoparticles via a [[diazonium]] reaction. The resulting catalyst was then used for the chemoselective oxidation of primary and secondary alcohols.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A. Sch\u00e4tz |author2=R. N. Grass |author3=W. J. Stark |author4=O. Reiser|journal=Chemistry: A European Journal|year=2008|volume=14|pages=8262\u20138266|doi= 10.1002/chem.200801001|pmid=18666291 |title=TEMPO Supported on Magnetic C/Co-Nanoparticles: A Highly Active and Recyclable Organocatalyst|first1=Alexander|issue=27}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Magnetic-chemistry-2.tif|frameless|center|550px|alt=TEMPO catalysis attached to magnetic nanoparticles]]\n\nThe catalytic reaction can be conducted in a [[continuous flow reactor]] instead of a [[batch reactor]] with no remains of the catalyst in the end product. Graphene coated cobalt nanoparticles have been used for that experiment since they exhibit a higher magnetization than [[Ferrite (magnet)|Ferrite]] nanoparticles, which is essential for a fast and clean separation via external magnetic field.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A. Sch\u00e4tz|author2=R. N. Grass |author3=Q. Kainz |author4=W. J. Stark |author5=O. Reiser |journal=Chemistry of Materials|year=2010|volume=22|pages=305\u2013310|doi=10.1021/cm9019099|title=Cu(II)\u2212Azabis(oxazoline) Complexes Immobilized on Magnetic Co/C Nanoparticles: Kinetic Resolution of 1,2-Diphenylethane-1,2-diol under Batch and Continuous-Flow Conditions|first1=Alexander|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Magnetic-chemistry-3.tif|frameless|center|550px|alt=Continuous flow catalysis]]\n\n=== Biomedical imaging ===\nThere are many applications for iron-oxide based nanoparticles in concert with [[magnetic resonance imaging]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Colombo | first1 = M | display-authors = etal   | year = 2012 | title = Biological Applications of Magnetic Nanoparticles | url = | journal = Chem Soc Rev | volume = 41 | issue = 11| pages = 4306\u201334 | doi=10.1039/c2cs15337h| pmid = 22481569 }}</ref> Magnetic CoPt nanoparticles are being used as an MRI contrast agent for transplanted [[neural stem cell]] detection.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Xiaoting Meng |author2=Hugh C. Seton |author3=Le T. Lu |author4=Ian A. Prior |author5=Nguyen T. K. Thanh |author6=Bing Song|journal=Nanoscale|year=2011|volume=3|pages=977\u2013984|doi=10.1039/C0NR00846J|bibcode = 2011Nanos...3..977M|title=Magnetic CoPt nanoparticles as MRI contrast agent for transplanted neural stem cells detection|first1=Xiaoting|issue=3|pmid=21293831 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cancer therapy ===\nIn magnetic fluid hyperthermia <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sharifi|first=Ibrahim|last2=Shokrollahi|first2=H.|last3=Amiri|first3=S.|date=2012-03-01|title=Ferrite-based magnetic nanofluids used in hyperthermia applications|journal=Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials|volume=324|issue=6|pages=903\u2013915|doi=10.1016/j.jmmm.2011.10.017|issn=0304-8853|bibcode=2012JMMM..324..903S}}</ref>, nanoparticles of different types like Iron oxide, magnetite, maghemite or even gold are injected in tumor and then subjected under a high frequency magnetic field. These nanoparticles produce heat that typically increases tumor temperature to 40-46&nbsp;\u00b0C, which can kill cancer cells.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.3109/02656736.2014.988661 | pmid=25523967 | volume=31 | issue=1 | title=Cylindrical agar gel with fluid flow subjected to an alternating magnetic field during hyperthermia | journal=International Journal of Hyperthermia | pages=33\u201339| year=2014 | last1=Javidi | first1=Mehrdad | last2=Heydari | first2=Morteza | last3=Attar | first3=Mohammad Mahdi | last4=Haghpanahi | first4=Mohammad | last5=Karimi | first5=Alireza | last6=Navidbakhsh | first6=Mahdi | last7=Amanpour | first7=Saeid }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=4289522 | pmid=25599061 | volume=4 | issue=4 | title=Evaluation of the effects of injection velocity and different gel concentrations on nanoparticles in hyperthermia therapy | year=2014 | journal=J Biomed Phys Eng | pages=151\u201362 | last1 = Javidi | first1 = M | last2 = Heydari | first2 = M | last3 = Karimi | first3 = A | last4 = Haghpanahi | first4 = M | last5 = Navidbakhsh | first5 = M | last6 = Razmkon | first6 = A}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1142/S0219519415500888|title = Magnetic Fluid Hyperthermia in a Cylindrical Gel Contains Water Flow|journal = Journal of Mechanics in Medicine and Biology|volume = 15|issue = 5|pages = 1550088|year = 2015|last1 = Heydari|first1 = Morteza|last2 = Javidi|first2 = Mehrdad|last3 = Attar|first3 = Mohammad Mahdi|last4 = Karimi|first4 = Alireza|last5 = Navidbakhsh|first5 = Mahdi|last6 = Haghpanahi|first6 = Mohammad|last7 = Amanpour|first7 = Saeid}}</ref>\nAnother major potential of magnetic nanoparticles is the ability to combine heat (hyperthermia) and drug release for a cancer treatment. Numerous studies have shown particle constructs that can be loaded with a drug cargo and magnetic nanoparticles.<ref name = \"Estelrich 2015\">{{cite journal | last1 = Estelrich | first1 = Joan | display-authors = etal  | year = 2015 | title = Iron Oxide Nanoparticles for Magnetically-Guided and Magnetically-Responsive Drug Delivery | url = | journal = Int. J. Mol. Sci. | volume = 16 | issue = 12| pages = 8070\u20138101 | doi = 10.3390/ijms16048070 | pmid = 25867479 | pmc = 4425068 }}</ref> The most prevalent construct is the \"Magnetoliposome\", which is a [[liposome]] with magnetic nanoparticles typically embedded in the lipid bilayer. Under an alternating magnetic field, the magnetic nanoparticles are heated, and this heat permeabilizes the membrane. This causes release of the loaded drug. This treatment option has a lot of potential as the combination of hyperthermia and drug release is likely to treat tumors better than either option alone, but it is still under development.\n\n=== Information storage ===\n{{see also|MRAM}}\nA promising candidate for high-density storage is the face-centered tetragonal phase FePt alloy. Grain sizes can be as small as 3 nanometers. If it's possible to modify the MNPs at this small scale, the information density that can be achieved with this media could easily surpass 1 Terabyte per square inch.<ref name=\"nanoscienceworks.org\"/>.\n\n=== Genetic engineering ===\nMagnetic nanoparticles can be used for a variety of genetics applications. One application is the rapid isolation of DNA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ernst|first=Constanze|last2=Bartel|first2=Alexander|last3=Elferink|first3=Johannes Wilhelmus|last4=Huhn|first4=Jennifer|last5=Eschbach|first5=Erik|last6=Sch\u00f6nfeld|first6=Kirsten|last7=Fe\u00dfler|first7=Andrea T.|last8=Oberheitmann|first8=Boris|last9=Schwarz|first9=Stefan|date=2019|title=Improved DNA extraction and purification with magnetic nanoparticles for the detection of methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|journal=Veterinary Microbiology|language=en|volume=230|pages=45\u201348|doi=10.1016/j.vetmic.2019.01.009|pmid=30827403}}</ref> and mRNA. In one application, the magnetic bead is attached to a poly T tail. When mixed with mRNA, the poly A tail of the mRNA will attach to the bead's poly T tail and the isolation takes place simply by placing a magnet on the side of the tube and pouring out the liquid. Magnetic beads have also been used in plasmid assembly. Rapid genetic circuit construction has been achieved by the sequential addition of genes onto a growing genetic chain, using nanobeads as an anchor. This method has been shown to be much faster than previous methods, taking less than an hour to create functional multi-gene constructs in vitro.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Chapter 14. Advances in the Preparation and Biomedical Applications of Magnetic Colloids|author1=A Elaissari |author2=J Chatterjee |author3=M Hamoudeh |author4=H Fessi |title=Structure and Functional Properties of Colloidal Systems|editor=Roque Hidalgo-\u00c5lvarez|publisher=CRC Press|year= 2010|pages =315\u2013337|isbn=978-1-4200-8447-4|doi=10.1201/9781420084474-c14}}</ref>\n\n== Physical modeling ==\nThere are a variety of mathematical models to describe the dynamics of the rotations of magnetic nanoparticles.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Reeves|first1=Daniel B.|title=Magnetic Characterization Techniques for Nanomaterials|date=2017|pages=121\u2013156|doi=10.1007/978-3-662-52780-1_4|publisher=Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg|language=en|isbn=978-3-662-52779-5|chapter=Nonlinear Nonequilibrium Simulations of Magnetic Nanoparticles}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reeves|first1=Daniel B.|last2=Weaver|first2=John B.|title=Approaches for Modeling Magnetic Nanoparticle Dynamics|journal=Critical Reviews in Biomedical Engineering|date=2014|volume=42|issue=1|doi=10.1615/CritRevBiomedEng.2014010845|pmid=25271360|pmc=4183932|language=English|issn=0278-940X|pages=85\u201393|arxiv=1505.02450}}</ref> Simple models include the Langevin function and the Stoner-Wohlfarth model which describe the magnetization of a nanoparticle at equilibrium. The Debye/Rosenszweig model can be used for low amplitude or high frequency oscillations of particles, which assumes linear response of the magnetization to an oscillating magnetic field.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrey|first1=J.|last2=Mehdaoui|first2=B.|last3=Respaud|first3=M.|title=Simple models for dynamic hysteresis loop calculations of magnetic single-domain nanoparticles: Application to magnetic hyperthermia optimization|journal=Journal of Applied Physics|date=15 April 2011|volume=109|issue=8|pages=083921\u2013083921\u201317|doi=10.1063/1.3551582|issn=0021-8979|bibcode=2011JAP...109h3921C|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01952248/file/JAP_Th%C3%A9orie_de_l%27hyperthermie.pdf|arxiv=1007.2009}}</ref> Non-equilibrium approaches include the Langevin equation formalism and the Fokker-Planck equation formalism, and these have been developed extensively to model applications such as magnetic nanoparticle hyperthermia, magnetic nanoparticle imaging (MPI),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Weizenecker|first1=J.|last2=Gleich|first2=B.|last3=Rahmer|first3=J.|last4=Dahnke|first4=H.|last5=Borgert|first5=J.|title=Three-dimensional real-time in vivo magnetic particle imaging|journal=Physics in Medicine and Biology|date=2009|volume=54|issue=5|pages=L1\u2013L10|doi=10.1088/0031-9155/54/5/L01|pmid=19204385|language=en|issn=0031-9155|bibcode=2009PMB....54L...1W|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/72744a865f7e6444c53e9b049025a2e97fd2fd75}}</ref> magnetic spectroscopy <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reeves|first1=Daniel B.|last2=Weaver|first2=John B.|title=Simulations of magnetic nanoparticle Brownian motion|journal=Journal of Applied Physics|date=15 December 2012|volume=112|issue=12|pages=124311|doi=10.1063/1.4770322|pmid=23319830|pmc=3537703|issn=0021-8979|bibcode=1998JChPh.109.4281T}}</ref> and biosensing <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zhang|first1=Xiaojuan|last2=Reeves|first2=Daniel B.|last3=Perreard|first3=Irina M.|last4=Kett|first4=Warren C.|last5=Griswold|first5=Karl E.|last6=Gimi|first6=Barjor|last7=Weaver|first7=John B.|title=Molecular sensing with magnetic nanoparticles using magnetic spectroscopy of nanoparticle Brownian motion|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|date=15 December 2013|volume=50|pages=441\u2013446|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2013.06.049|pmid=23896525|pmc=3844855}}</ref> etc.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Iron oxide nanoparticles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.fml.ethz.ch FML \u2013 Functional Materials Laboratory of the ETH Z\u00fcrich]\n* [http://nanos-sci.com/technology.html Properties and use of magnetic nanoparticle clusters (magnetic nanobeads)]\n* [http://news.cnet.com/8301-27083_3-10446292-247.html Magnetic nanoparticles target human cancer cells]\n* [http://www.physorg.com/news198570612.html Magnetic Nanoparticles Remove Ovarian Cancer Cells from the Abdominal Cavity]\n* Wiedwald, U. and Ziemann, P. (Ed.): [http://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano/browse/singleSeries.htm?sn=1 Properties and applications of magnetic nanoparticles], Thematic Series in the Open Access Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology.\n* [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0254058418306047 Effects of surfactant on the structural and magnetic properties of hydrothermally synthesized NiFe2O4 nanoparticles]\n== Bibliography ==\n* Catinon, M., Ayrault, S., Boudouma, O., Bordier, L., Agnello, G., Reynaud, S., & Tissut, M. (2014). ''Isolation of technogenic magnetic particles''. Science of the Total Environment, 475, 39-47 ([https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0048969713015647 abstract]).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magnetic Nanoparticles}}\n[[Category:Magnetism]]\n[[Category:Nanoparticles by physical property]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Synthesized magnetic particles of diameter under 100 nanometers with biomedical applications}}\n{{Primary sources|date=August 2016}}\n\n'''Magnetic nanoparticles''' are a class of [[nanoparticle]] that can be manipulated using [[magnetic field]]s. Such particles commonly consist of two components, a magnetic material, often [[iron]], [[nickel]] and [[cobalt]], and a [[chemical]] component that has functionality. While nanoparticles are smaller than 1 micrometer in diameter (typically 1\u2013100 nanometers), the larger [[microbeads]] are 0.5\u2013500 micrometer in diameter. Magnetic nanoparticle clusters that are composed of a number of individual magnetic nanoparticles are known as magnetic nanobeads with a diameter of 50\u2013200 nanometers.<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\">{{cite journal|last1=Tadic|first1=Marin|last2=Kralj|first2=Slavko|last3=Jagodic|first3=Marko|last4=Hanzel|first4=Darko|last5=Makovec|first5=Darko|title=Magnetic properties of novel superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoclusters and their peculiarity under annealing treatment|journal=Applied Surface Science|date=December 2014|volume=322|pages=255\u2013264|doi=10.1016/j.apsusc.2014.09.181|bibcode = 2014ApSS..322..255T }}</ref><ref>Magnetic Nanomaterials, Editors: S H Bossmann, H Wang, Royal Society of Chemistry, Cambridge 2017, https://pubs.rsc.org/en/content/ebook/978-1-78801-037-5</ref>Magnetic nanoparticle clusters are a basis for their further magnetic assembly into [[magnetic nanochains]].<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Makovec|first2=Darko|title=Magnetic Assembly of Superparamagnetic Iron Oxide Nanoparticle Clusters into Nanochains and Nanobundles|journal=ACS Nano|date=27 October 2015|volume=9|issue=10|pages=9700\u20139707|doi=10.1021/acsnano.5b02328|pmid=26394039}}</ref> The magnetic nanoparticles have been the focus of much research recently because they possess attractive properties which could see potential use in [[catalysis]] including [[nanomaterial-based catalyst]]s,<ref>{{cite journal |author1=A.-H. Lu |author2=W. Schmidt |author3=N. Matoussevitch |author4=H. B\u00f6nnemann |author5=B. Spliethoff |author6=B. Tesche |author7=E. Bill |author8=W. Kiefer |author9=F. Sch\u00fcth |date=August 2004 |title=Nanoengineering of a Magnetically Separable Hydrogenation Catalyst |journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition |volume=43 |issue=33 |pages=4303\u20134306 |doi=10.1002/anie.200454222 |pmid=15368378}}</ref> [[biomedicine]] <ref>{{cite journal |author1=A. K. Gupta |author2=M. Gupta |date=June 2005 |title=Synthesis and surface engineering of iron oxide nanoparticles for biomedical applications |journal=Biomaterials  |volume=26 |issue=18 |pages=3995\u20134021 |doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2004.10.012 |pmid=15626447}}</ref> and tissue specific targeting,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Ramaswamy|first1=B|last2=Kulkarni|first2=SD|last3=Villar|first3=PS|last4=Smith|first4=RS|last5=Eberly|first5=C|last6=Araneda|first6=RC|last7=Depireux|first7=DA|last8=Shapiro|first8=B|title=Movement of magnetic nanoparticles in brain tissue: mechanisms and safety|journal=Nanomedicine: Nanotechnology, Biology and Medicine|date=24 June 2015|doi=10.1016/j.nano.2015.06.003|pmid=26115639|volume=11|issue=7|pages=1821\u20139|pmc=4586396}}</ref> magnetically tunable colloidal [[photonic crystals]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=He|first1=Le|last2=Wang|first2=Mingsheng|last3=Ge|first3=Jianping|last4=Yin|first4=Yadong|title=Magnetic Assembly Route to Colloidal Responsive Photonic Nanostructures|journal=Accounts of Chemical Research|date=18 September 2012|volume=45|issue=9|pages=1431\u20131440|doi=10.1021/ar200276t|pmid=22578015|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/1274g7zx}}</ref> [[microfluidics]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kavre|first1=Ivna|last2=Kostevc|first2=Gregor|last3=Kralj|first3=Slavko|last4=Vilfan|first4=Andrej|last5=Babi\u010d|first5=Du\u0161an|title=Fabrication of magneto-responsive microgears based on magnetic nanoparticle embedded PDMS|journal=RSC Advances|date=13 August 2014|volume=4|issue=72|pages=38316\u201338322|doi=10.1039/C4RA05602G}}</ref> [[magnetic resonance imaging]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mornet|first1=S.|last2=Vasseur|first2=S.|last3=Grasset|first3=F.|last4=Veverka|first4=P.|last5=Goglio|first5=G.|last6=Demourgues|first6=A.|last7=Portier|first7=J.|last8=Pollert|first8=E.|last9=Duguet|first9=E.|title=Magnetic nanoparticle design for medical applications|journal=Progress in Solid State Chemistry|date=July 2006|volume=34|issue=2\u20134|pages=237\u2013247|doi=10.1016/j.progsolidstchem.2005.11.010}}</ref> [[magnetic particle imaging]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=B. Gleich |author2=J. Weizenecker |journal=  Nature |volume=435|pages= 1214\u20131217 |doi=10.1038/nature03808 |pmid=15988521 |year=2005 |title=Tomographic imaging using the nonlinear response of magnetic particles |issue=7046 |bibcode = 2005Natur.435.1214G }}</ref> [[data storage device|data storage]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hyeon|first1=Taeghwan|title=Chemical synthesis of magnetic nanoparticles|journal=Chemical Communications|date=3 April 2003|issue=8|pages=927\u2013934|doi=10.1039/B207789B|pmid=12744306|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/785c6c1445e1a2d54389fa95954b525f26798cce}}</ref><ref name=\"nanoscienceworks.org\">Natalie A. Frey and Shouheng Sun [https://web.archive.org/web/20111004094259/http://www.nanoscienceworks.org/publications/just-in-print/K10915_chapter3%20(2).pdf Magnetic Nanoparticle for Information Storage Applications]</ref> [[environmental remediation]],<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Elliott|first1=Daniel W.|last2=Zhang|first2=Wei-xian|title=Field Assessment of Nanoscale Bimetallic Particles for Groundwater Treatment|journal=Environmental Science & Technology|date=December 2001|volume=35|issue=24|pages=4922\u20134926|doi=10.1021/es0108584|pmid=11775172|bibcode = 2001EnST...35.4922E }}</ref> [[nanofluids]],<ref>{{cite journal |author1=J. Philip |author2=Shima.P.D. B. Raj |year=2006 |title= Nanofluid with tunable thermal properties |journal= Applied Physics Letters |volume=92 |issue=4 | pages=043108| doi=10.1063/1.2838304|bibcode = 2008ApPhL..92d3108P }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1088/1361-6463/aa4f92|title = Self pumping magnetic cooling|journal = Journal of Physics D: Applied Physics|volume = 50|issue = 3|pages = 03LT03|year = 2017|last1 = Chaudhary|first1 = V.|last2 = Wang|first2 = Z.|last3 = Ray|first3 = A.|last4 = Sridhar|first4 = I.|last5 = Ramanujan|first5 = R. V.|bibcode = 2017JPhD...50cLT03C}}</ref>, optical filters,<ref>{{cite journal |author1= J.Philip |author2= T.J.Kumar |author3= P.Kalyanasundaram |author4= B.Raj|year=2003 |title= Tunable Optical Filter |journal= Measurement Science and Technology |volume=14 |issue=8 | pages=1289\u20131294 |doi=10.1088/0957-0233/14/8/314|bibcode = 2003MeScT..14.1289P }}</ref>  defect sensor <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mahendran | first1 = V. | title = Nanofluid based opticalsensor for rapid visual inspection of defects in ferromagnetic materials | url = | journal = Appl. Phys. Lett. | volume = 100 | issue = 7| page = 073104 | doi = 10.1063/1.3684969 |bibcode = 2012ApPhL.100g3104M | year = 2012 }}</ref>, magnetic cooling<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chaudhary |first1=V. |last2=Ramanujan |first2=R. V. |title=Magnetocaloric Properties of Fe-Ni-Cr Nanoparticles for Active Cooling |journal=Scientific Reports |date=11 October 2016 |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=35156 |doi=10.1038/srep35156 |pmid=27725754 |pmc=5057077 |bibcode=2016NatSR...635156C }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chaudhary |first1=V. |last2=Chen |first2=X. |last3=Ramanujan |first3=R.V. |title=Iron and manganese based magnetocaloric materials for near room temperature thermal management |journal=Progress in Materials Science |date=February 2019 |volume=100 |pages=64\u201398 |doi=10.1016/j.pmatsci.2018.09.005 }}</ref> and cation sensors.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Philip | first1 = V. Mahendran | last2 = Felicia | first2 = Leona J. | year = 2013 | title = A Simple, In-Expensive and Ultrasensitive Magnetic Nanofluid Based Sensor for Detection of Cations, Ethanol and Ammonia | url = | journal = Journal of Nanofluids| volume = 2 | issue = 2| pages = 112\u2013119 | doi = 10.1166/jon.2013.1050 }}</ref>\n\n== Properties ==\nThe physical and chemical properties of magnetic nanoparticles largely depend on the synthesis method and chemical structure. In most cases, the particles range from 1 to 100&nbsp;nm in size and may display [[superparamagnetism]].<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\">{{cite journal |author1=A.-H. Lu |author2=E. L. Salabas |author3=F. Sch\u00fcth |journal =Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.|year= 2007|volume= 46|pages=1222\u20131244 |doi=10.1002/anie.200602866 |pmid=17278160 |title=Magnetic Nanoparticles: Synthesis, Protection, Functionalization, and Application |issue=8}}</ref>\n\n== Types of magnetic nanoparticles ==\n\n=== Oxides: ferrites ===\n[[Ferrite (magnet)|Ferrite]] nanoparticles or [[iron oxide nanoparticles]] ([[iron oxides]] in crystal structure of [[maghemite]] or [[magnetite]]) are the most explored magnetic nanoparticles up to date. Once the ferrite particles become smaller than 128&nbsp;nm<ref name=\"Angew.review\">{{cite journal|last=An-Hui Lu|author2=E. L. Salabas |author3=Ferdi Sch\u00fcth |journal=Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.|year=2007|volume=46|pages=1222\u20131244|doi= 10.1002/anie.200602866|pmid=17278160 |title=Magnetic Nanoparticles: Synthesis, Protection, Functionalization, and Application|first1=An-Hui|issue=8}}</ref> they become [[superparamagnetic]] which prevents self agglomeration since they exhibit their magnetic behavior only when an external magnetic field is applied. The magnetic moment of ferrite nanoparticles can be greatly increased by controlled clustering of a number of individual superparamagnetic nanoparticles into superparamagnetic nanoparticle clusters, namely [[magnetic nanobeads]].<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\" /> With the external magnetic field switched off, the [[remanence]] falls back to zero. Just like non-magnetic oxide nanoparticles, the surface of ferrite nanoparticles is often modified by [[surfactant]]s, [[silica]],<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\" /> [[silicones]] or [[phosphoric acid]] derivatives to increase their stability in solution.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kim, DK|journal=Chemistry of Materials|year=2003|volume=15|issue=8|pages=1617\u20131627|doi=10.1021/cm001253u|author2=Mikhaylova, M|last3=Zhang|first3=Y|display-authors=2|title=Anchoring of Phosphonate and Phosphinate Coupling Molecules on Titania Particles|first1=G.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Maghemite silica nanoparticle cluster.jpg|right|thumbnail|400px|alt=Maghemite nanoparticle cluster with silica shell.|[[Transmission electron microscopy|TEM]] image of a maghemite magnetic nanoparticle cluster with silica shell.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/><ref>http://nanos-sci.com/technology.html Properties and use of magnetic nanoparticle clusters (magnetic nanobeads)</ref>]]\n\n=== Ferrites with a shell===\nThe surface of a maghemite or magnetite magnetic nanoparticle is relatively inert and does not usually allow strong covalent bonds with functionalization molecules. However, the reactivity of the magnetic nanoparticles can be improved by coating a layer of [[silica]] onto their surface.<ref name=\"Kralj et al 2010 Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Makovec|first2=Darko|last3=\u010campelj|first3=Stanislav|last4=Drofenik|first4=Miha|title=Producing ultra-thin silica coatings on iron-oxide nanoparticles to improve their surface reactivity|journal=Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials|date=July 2010|volume=322|issue=13|pages=1847\u20131853|doi=10.1016/j.jmmm.2009.12.038|bibcode = 2010JMMM..322.1847K }}</ref> The [[silica]] shell can be easily modified with various surface functional groups via covalent bonds between organo-silane molecules and silica shell.<ref name=\"Kralj et al 2010 Journal of Nanoparticle Research\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Drofenik|first2=Miha|last3=Makovec|first3=Darko|title=Controlled surface functionalization of silica-coated magnetic nanoparticles with terminal amino and carboxyl groups|journal=Journal of Nanoparticle Research|date=16 December 2010|volume=13|issue=7|pages=2829\u20132841|doi=10.1007/s11051-010-0171-4|bibcode=2011JNR....13.2829K}}</ref> In addition, some [[fluorescent dye]] molecules can be covalently bonded to the functionalized [[silica]] shell.<ref name=\"Kralj 2012 Journal of Nanoparticle Research\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Rojnik|first2=Matija|last3=Romih|first3=Rok|last4=Jagodi\u010d|first4=Marko|last5=Kos|first5=Janko|last6=Makovec|first6=Darko|title=Effect of surface charge on the cellular uptake of fluorescent magnetic nanoparticles|journal=Journal of Nanoparticle Research|date=7 September 2012|volume=14|issue=10|pages=1151|doi=10.1007/s11051-012-1151-7|bibcode=2012JNR....14.1151K}}</ref>\n\nFerrite nanoparticle clusters with narrow size distribution consisting of superparamagnetic oxide nanoparticles (~ 80 maghemite superparamagnetic nanoparticles per bead) coated with a silica shell have several advantages over metallic nanoparticles:<ref name=\"Tadic et al 2014\"/>\n\n*Higher chemical stability (crucial for biomedical applications)\n*Narrow size distribution (crucial for biomedical applications)\n*Higher colloidal stability since they do not magnetically agglomerate\n*Magnetic moment can be tuned with the nanoparticle cluster size\n*Retained superparamagnetic properties (independent of the nanoparticle cluster size)\n*Silica surface enables straightforward covalent functionalization\n\n=== Metallic ===\nMetallic nanoparticles may be beneficial for some technical applications due to their higher magnetic moment whereas oxides ([[maghemite]], [[magnetite]]) would be beneficial for biomedical applications. This also implies that for the same moment, metallic nanoparticles can be made smaller than their oxide counterparts. On the other hand, metallic nanoparticles have the great disadvantage of being [[pyrophoric]] and reactive to [[oxidizing agents]] to various degrees. This makes their handling difficult and enables unwanted side reactions which makes them less appropriate for biomedical applications. Colloid formation for metallic particles is also much more challenging.\n\n[[File:Cobalt-graphene-nanoparticle.tif|frame|upright|alt=Cobalt nanoparticle with graphene shell.|Cobalt nanoparticle with graphene shell (note: The individual [[graphene]] layers are visible)<ref name=\"R.N. Grass 2007 4909\u201312\">{{cite journal|last=R.N. Grass |author2=E.K. Athanassiou |author3=W.J. Stark|journal=Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.|year=2007|volume=46|pages=4909\u201312|doi=10.1002/anie.200700613|title=Covalently Functionalized Cobalt Nanoparticles as a Platform for Magnetic Separations in Organic Synthesis|first1=Robert N.|issue=26|pmid=17516598}}</ref>]]\n\n=== Metallic with a shell ===\nThe metallic core of magnetic nanoparticles may be passivated by gentle oxidation, surfactants, polymers and precious metals.<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/> In an oxygen environment, Co nanoparticles form an anti-ferromagnetic CoO layer on the surface of the Co nanoparticle. Recently, work has explored the synthesis and exchange bias effect in these Co core CoO shell nanoparticles with a gold outer shell.<ref name=\"Johnsonj.mater.chem.2010\">\n{{cite journal|last=Johnson|first=Stephanie H. |author2=C.L. Johnson |author3=S.J. May |author4=S. Hirsch |author5=M.W. Cole |author6=J.E. Spanier|title=Co@CoO@Au core-multi-shell nanocrystals|journal=Journal of Materials Chemistry|year=2010|volume=20|pages=439\u2013443|doi=10.1039/b919610b|issue=3}}</ref>\nNanoparticles with a magnetic core consisting either of elementary [[Iron]] or [[Cobalt]] with a nonreactive shell made of [[graphene]] have been synthesized recently.<ref name=\"j.mater.chem.2006\">{{cite journal|last=R. N. Grass|author2=W. J. Stark|journal=J. Mater. Chem.|year=2006|issue=19|page=1825|doi=10.1039/B601013J|title=Gas phase synthesis of fcc-cobalt nanoparticles|first1=Robert N.|volume=16|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/663a70017aa8db59caaf080f774f74ce7e75b01f}}</ref> The advantages compared to ferrite or elemental nanoparticles are:\n* Higher [[magnetization]]\n* Higher stability in [[acidic]] and [[Base (chemistry)|basic]] solution as well as [[organic solvents]]\n* Chemistry<ref name=\"R.N. Grass 2007 4909\u201312\"/>  on the graphene surface via methods already known for [[carbon nanotubes]]\n\n== Synthesis ==\n\nSeveral methods exist for preparing magnetic [[nanoparticle]].\n\n=== Co-precipitation ===\n{{main|Co-precipitation}}\nCo-precipitation is a facile and convenient way to synthesize iron oxides (either Fe<sub>3</sub>O<sub>4</sub> or \u03b3-Fe<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>) from aqueous Fe<sup>2+</sup>/Fe<sup>3+</sup> salt solutions by the addition of a base under inert\natmosphere at room temperature or at elevated temperature. The size, shape, and composition of the magnetic nanoparticles very much depends on the type of salts used (e.g.chlorides, sulfates, nitrates), the Fe<sup>2+</sup>/Fe<sup>3+</sup> ratio, the reaction [[temperature]], the [[pH]] value and [[ionic strength]] of the media,<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/> and the mixing rate with the base solution used to provoke the precipitation.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fang | first1 = Mei | last2 = Str\u00f6m | first2 = Valter | last3 = Olsson | first3 = Richard T. | last4 = Belova | first4 = Lyubov | last5 = Rao | first5 = K. V. | title = Rapid mixing: A route to synthesize magnetite nanoparticles with high moment| url = | journal = Appl. Phys. Lett. | volume = 99 | issue = 22| page = 222501 | doi=10.1063/1.3662965|bibcode = 2011ApPhL..99v2501F | year = 2011 }}</ref> The co-precipitation approach has been used extensively to produce ferrite nanoparticles of controlled sizes and magnetic properties.<ref>{{cite journal |author1= G.Gnanaprakash |author2=S.Ayyappan |author3=T.Jayakumar |author4=John Philip |author5=Baldev Raj  |year=2006 |title= A simple method to produce magnetic nanoparticles with enhanced alpha to gamma-Fe2O3 phase transition temperature |journal= Nanotechnology |volume=17 |issue=23 | pages=5851\u20135857|bibcode = 2006Nanot..17.5851G |doi = 10.1088/0957-4484/17/23/023 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=G. Gnanaprakash |author2=John Philip |author3=T. Jayakumar |author4=Baldev Raj |year=2007 |title= Effect of Digestion Time and Alkali Addition Rate on the Physical Properties of Magnetite Nanoparticles |journal= J. Phys. Chem. B   |volume=111 |issue=28 | pages=7978\u20137986 |doi=10.1021/jp071299b|pmid=17580856 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=S.Ayyappan, John Philip  |author2=Baldev Raj  |lastauthoramp=yes |year=2009 |title= Solvent polarity effect on physical properties of CoFe2O3 nanoparticles |journal= J. Phys. Chem. C   |volume=113 |issue=2  | pages=590\u2013596 |doi=10.1021/jp8083875}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author1=S. Ayyappan |author2=S. Mahadevan |author3=P. Chandramohan |author4=M. P.Srinivasan |author5=John Philip |author6=Baldev Raj |year=2010 |title= Influence of Co2 Ion Concentration on the Size, Magnetic Properties, and Purity of CoFe2O4 Spinel Ferrite Nanoparticles |journal= J. Phys. Chem. C   |volume=114 |issue=14 | pages=6334\u20136341 |doi=10.1021/jp911966p}}</ref> A variety of experimental arrangements have been reported to facilitate continuous and large\u2013scale co\u2013precipitation of magnetic particles by rapid mixing.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Fun Chin | first1 = Suk | last2 = Iyer | first2 = K. Swaminathan | last3 = Raston | first3 = Colin L. | authorlink3 = Colin Raston | last4 = Saunders | first4 = Martin | year = 2008 | title = Size Selective Synthesis of Superparamagnetic Nanoparticles in Thin Fluids under Continuous Flow Conditions| url = http://ir.unimas.my/9899/1/Size%20Selective%20Synthesis%20of%20Superparamagnetic%20Nanoparticles%20in%20Thin%20Fluids%20under%20Continuous%20Flow%20Conditions%20%28abstract%29.pdf| journal = Adv. Funct. Mater. | volume = 18 | issue = 6| pages = 922\u2013927 | doi=10.1002/adfm.200701101}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Raston |first1=CL |last2=Saunders |first2=M |last3=Smith |first3=N |last4=Woodward |first4=R |title=Synthesis of Magnetic Nanoparticles Using Spinning Disc Processing |journal=TechConnect Briefs |date=7 May 2006 |volume=1 |issue=2006 |pages=343\u2013346 |url=https://briefs.techconnect.org/papers/synthesis-of-magnetic-nanoparticles-using-spinning-disc-processing/ }}</ref> Recently, the growth rate of the magnetic nanoparticles was measured in real-time during the precipitation of magnetite nanoparticles by an integrated AC magnetic susceptometer within the mixing zone of the reactants.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Str\u00f6m |first1=Valter |last2=Olsson |first2=Richard T. |last3=Rao |first3=K. V. |title=Real-time monitoring of the evolution of magnetism during precipitation of superparamagnetic nanoparticles for bioscience applications |journal=Journal of Materials Chemistry |date=2010 |volume=20 |issue=20 |pages=4168 |doi=10.1039/c0jm00043d }}</ref>\n\n=== Thermal decomposition ===\n{{main|Thermal decomposition}}\nMagnetic nanocrystals with smaller size can essentially be synthesized through the thermal decomposition of alkaline organometallic compounds in high-boiling organic solvents containing stabilizing surfactants.<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sharifi|first=Ibrahim|last2=Zamanian|first2=Ali|last3=Behnamghader|first3=Aliasghar|date=2016-08-15|title=Synthesis and characterization of Fe0.6Zn0.4Fe2O4 ferrite magnetic nanoclusters using simple thermal decomposition method|journal=Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials|volume=412|pages=107\u2013113|doi=10.1016/j.jmmm.2016.03.091|issn=0304-8853|bibcode=2016JMMM..412..107S}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Monfared|first=A. H.|last2=Zamanian|first2=A.|last3=Beygzadeh|first3=M.|last4=Sharifi|first4=I.|last5=Mozafari|first5=M.|date=2017-02-05|title=A rapid and efficient thermal decomposition approach for the synthesis of manganese-zinc/oleylamine core/shell ferrite nanoparticles|journal=Journal of Alloys and Compounds|volume=693|pages=1090\u20131095|doi=10.1016/j.jallcom.2016.09.253|issn=0925-8388}}</ref>\n\n=== Microemulsion ===\n{{main|Microemulsion}}\nUsing the microemulsion technique, metallic cobalt, cobalt/platinum alloys, and gold-coated cobalt/platinum nanoparticles have been synthesized in reverse [[micelles]] of cetyltrimethlyammonium bromide, using 1-butanol as the cosurfactant and octane as the oil phase.,<ref name=\"Angew.chem.2007\"/><ref>{{cite journal |author1= S S.Rana |author2=J. Philip |author3=B.Raj  |year=2010 |title= Micelle based synthesis of Cobalt Ferrite nanoparticles and its characterization using Fourier Transform Infrared Transmission Spectrometry and Thermogravimetry |journal= Materials Chemistry and Physics   |volume=124 | pages=264\u2013269 |doi=10.1016/j.matchemphys.2010.06.029}}</ref>\n\n=== Flame spray synthesis ===\nUsing [[Flame spray|flame spray pyrolysis ]]<ref name=\"j.mater.chem.2006\"/><ref>{{cite journal|last=E. K. Athanassiou|author2=R. N. Grass |author3=W. J. Stark |journal=Aerosol. Sci. Tech.|year=2010|volume=44|issue=2|pages=161\u201372|doi=10.1080/02786820903449665|title=Chemical Aerosol Engineering as a Novel Tool for Material Science: From Oxides to Salt and Metal Nanoparticles|first1=Evagelos K.|bibcode=2010AerST..44..161A}}</ref>  and varying the reaction conditions, oxides, metal or carbon coated nanoparticles are produced at a rate of > 30 g/h .\n\n{|\n| [[File:Flame-spray-synthesis.JPG|frame|center|alt=Various flame spray conditions and their impact on the resulting nanoparticles|Various flame spray conditions and their impact on the resulting [[nanoparticles]]]]\n| [[File:Flame-spray-synthesis-2.JPG|frame|center|alt=Operational layout differences between conventional and reducing flame spray synthesis|Operational layout differences between conventional and reducing flame spray synthesis]]\n|}\n\n== Potential applications ==\nA wide variety of potential applications have been envisaged.  Since magnetic nanoparticles are expensive to produce, there is interest in their recycling or for highly specialized applications.\n\nThe potential and versatility of magnetic chemistry arises from the fast and easy separation of the magnetic nanoparticles, eliminating tedious and costly [[separation processes]] usually applied in chemistry. Furthermore, the magnetic nanoparticles can be guided via a magnetic field to the desired location which could, for example, enable pinpoint precision in fighting cancer.\n\n=== Medical diagnostics and treatments ===\n\nMagnetic nanoparticles have been examined for use in an [[experimental cancer treatment]] called [[magnetic hyperthermia]] <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rabias | first1 = I. | display-authors = etal   | title = Rapid magnetic heating treatment by highly charged maghemite nanoparticles on Wistar rats exocranial glioma tumors at microliter volume| url = | journal = Biomicrofluidics | volume = 4 | issue = 2| page = 024111 | doi = 10.1063/1.3449089 | pmid = 20697578 | pmc = 2917883| year = 2010 }}</ref> in which an alternating magnetic field (AMF) is used to heat the nanoparticles. To achieve sufficient magnetic nanoparticle heating, the AMF typically has a frequency between 100\u2013500&nbsp;kHz, although significant research has been done at lower frequencies as well as frequencies as high as 10&nbsp;MHz, with the amplitude of the field usually between 8-16kAm<sup>\u22121</sup>.<ref name = \"Kumar\">{{cite journal | pmid = 21447363 | doi=10.1016/j.addr.2011.03.008 | pmc=3138885 | volume=63 | issue=9 | title=Magnetic nanomaterials for hyperthermia-based therapy and controlled drug delivery | year=2011 | journal=Adv. Drug Deliv. Rev. | pages=789\u2013808 | last1 = Kumar | first1 = CS | last2 = Mohammad | first2 = F}}</ref>\n\nAffinity ligands such as epidermal growth factor ([[Epidermal growth factor|EGF]]), [[folic acid]], [[aptamer]]s, [[lectin]]s etc. can be attached to the magnetic nanoparticle surface with the use of various chemistries. This enables targeting of magnetic nanoparticles to specific tissues or cells.<ref name=\"Kralj et al 2013 EGF\">{{cite journal|last1=Kralj|first1=Slavko|last2=Rojnik|first2=Matija|last3=Kos|first3=Janko|last4=Makovec|first4=Darko|title=Targeting EGFR-overexpressed A431 cells with EGF-labeled silica-coated magnetic nanoparticles|journal=Journal of Nanoparticle Research|date=26 April 2013|volume=15|issue=5|pages=1666|doi=10.1007/s11051-013-1666-6|bibcode=2013JNR....15.1666K}}</ref> This strategy is used in cancer research to target and treat tumors in combination with [[magnetic hyperthermia]] or nanoparticle-delivered [[cancer drug]]s. Despite research efforts, however, the accumulation of nanoparticles inside of cancer tumors of all types is sub-optimal, even with affinity ligands. Willhelm et al. conducted a broad analysis of nanoparticle delivery to tumors and concluded that the median amount of injected dose reaching a solid tumor is only 0.7%.<ref name = \"Willhelm 2016\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/natrevmats.2016.14|title=Analysis of nanoparticle delivery to tumours|journal=Nature Reviews Materials|volume=1|issue=5|pages=16014|year=2016|last1=Wilhelm|first1=Stefan|last2=Tavares|first2=Anthony J.|last3=Dai|first3=Qin|last4=Ohta|first4=Seiichi|last5=Audet|first5=Julie|last6=Dvorak|first6=Harold F.|last7=Chan|first7=Warren C. W.|bibcode=2016NatRM...116014W}}</ref> The challenge of accumulating large amounts of nanoparticles inside of tumors is arguably the biggest obstacle facing nanomedicine in general. While direct injection is used in some cases, intravenous injection is most often preferred to obtain a good distribution of particles throughout the tumor. Magnetic nanoparticles have a distinct advantage in that they can accumulate in desired regions via magnetically guided delivery, although this technique still needs further development to achieve optimal delivery to solid tumors.\n\nAnother potential treatment of cancer includes attaching magnetic nanoparticles to free-floating cancer cells, allowing them to be captured and carried out of the body. The treatment has been tested in the laboratory on mice and will be looked at in survival studies.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Scarberry KE, Dickerson EB, McDonald JF, Zhang ZJ |year=2008|title=Magnetic Nanoparticle-Peptide Conjugates for in Vitro and in Vivo Targeting and Extraction of Cancer Cells |journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society |pmid=18611005 |doi=10.1021/ja801969b |volume=130 |pages=10258\u201362 |issue=31 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.newswise.com/articles/view/542665 Using Magnetic Nanoparticles to Combat Cancer] Newswise, Retrieved on July 17, 2008.</ref>\n\nMagnetic nanoparticles can be used for the detection of cancer. Blood can be inserted onto a microfluidic chip with magnetic nanoparticles in it. These magnetic nanoparticles are trapped inside due to an externally applied magnetic field as the blood is free to flow through. The magnetic nanoparticles are coated with antibodies targeting cancer cells or proteins.  The magnetic nanoparticles can be recovered and the attached cancer-associated molecules can be assayed to test for their existence.\n\nMagnetic nanoparticles can be conjugated with carbohydrates and used for detection of bacteria. Iron oxide particles have been used for the detection of Gram negative bacteria like [[Escherichia coli]] and for detection of Gram positive bacteria like [[Streptococcus suis]]<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Parera Pera N |author2=Kouki A. |author3=Finne J. |author4=Pieters R. J. |year=2010  |title=Detection of pathogenic Streptococcus suis bacteria using magnetic glycoparticles |journal= Organic & Biomolecular Chemistry|doi=10.1039/C000819B |pmid=20448902 |volume=8 |pages=2425\u20132429 |issue=10 |url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/f5c71a62e8892e142c8e7768b7b905a3d2e151a9 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsc.org/Publishing/Journals/cb/Volume/2010/05/an_attractive_method.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121021043001/http://www.rsc.org/Publishing/Journals/cb/Volume/2010/05/an_attractive_method.asp |archivedate=21 October 2012 |title=An attractive method for bacteria detection |date=30 March 2010 |work=Highlights in Chemical Biology |first1=David |last1=Barden }}</ref>\n\n=== Magnetic immunoassay ===\n[[Magnetic immunoassay]]<ref>[http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html Magnetic immunoassays: A new paradigm in POCT] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080830062331/http://www.devicelink.com/ivdt/archive/08/07/008.html |date=2008-08-30 }} IVDt, July/August 2008.</ref> (MIA) is a novel type of diagnostic immunoassay utilizing [[magnetic nanobeads]] as labels in lieu of conventional, enzymes, radioisotopes or fluorescent moieties. This assay involves the specific binding of an antibody to its antigen, where a magnetic label is conjugated to one element of the pair. The presence of [[magnetic nanobeads]] is then detected by a magnetic reader (magnetometer) which measures the magnetic field change induced by the beads. The signal measured by the magnetometer is proportional to the analyte (virus, toxin, bacteria, cardiac marker, etc.) quantity in the initial sample.\n\n=== Waste water treatment ===\nThanks to the easy separation by applying a magnetic field and the very large [[surface to volume ratio]], magnetic nanoparticles have a potential for treatment of contaminated water.<ref>{{cite journal|last=F.M. Koehler |author2=M. Rossier |author3=M. Waelle |author4=E.K. Athanassiou |author5=L.K. Limbach |author6=R.N. Grass |author7=D. G\u00fcnther |author8=W.J. Stark|journal=Chem. Commun.|year=2009|volume=32|pages=4862\u20134|doi=10.1039/B909447D|pmid=19652806 |title=Magnetic EDTA: Coupling heavy metal chelators to metal nanomagnets for rapid removal of cadmium, lead and copper from contaminated water|first1=Fabian M.|issue=32|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/1b7c55dfcb27958f6eedd5480a8c5c2ebc6e26f4 }}</ref>\nIn this method, attachment of EDTA-like chelators to carbon coated metal nanomagnets results in a magnetic reagent for the rapid removal of heavy metals from solutions or contaminated water by three orders of magnitude to concentrations as low as micrograms per Litre. [[Magnetic nanobeads]] or nanoparticle clusters composed of FDA-approved oxide superparamagnetic nanoparticles (e.g. [[maghemite]], [[magnetite]]) hold much potential for waste water treatment since they express excellent [[biocompatibility]] which concerning the [[environmental impacts]] of the material is an advantage compared to metallic nanoparticles.\n\n=== Supported enzymes and peptides===\nEnzymes, proteins, and other biologically and chemically active substances have been immobilized on magnetic nanoparticles.<ref name=\"biocatalyst\">{{cite journal|last=Huang-Hao Yang |author2=Shu-Qiong Zhang |author3=Xiao-Lan Chen |author4=Zhi-Xia Zhuang |author5=Jin-Gou Xu |author6=Xiao-Ru Wang|journal=Analytical Chemistry|year=2004|volume=76|pages=1316\u20131321|doi=10.1021/ac034920m|title=Magnetite-Containing Spherical Silica Nanoparticles for Biocatalysis and Bioseparations|first1=Huang-Hao|issue=5|pmid=14987087}}</ref>  \nThe immobilization of enzymes on inexpensive, non-toxic and easily-synthesized iron magnetic\nnanoparticles (MNP) has shown great promise due to more stable proteins, better product yield, ease of protein purification and multiple usage as a result of their magnetic susceptibility <ref>Siddiqui KS, Shemsi AM, Guerriero G, Najnin T, Taha, Ertan H, 2017. Biotechnological improvements of cold-adapted enzymes: commercialization via an integrated approach. In: Margesin, Rosa (Ed.), Psychrophiles: From Biodiversity to Biotechnology, Springer-Verlag, pp. 477\u2013512.</ref>.\nThey are of interest as possible supports for [[solid phase synthesis]].<ref name=\"magnetic.peptide\">{{cite journal|last=K.Nor\u00e9n|author2=M. Kempe|journal=International Journal of Peptide Research and Therapeutics|year=2009|volume=15|issue=4|pages=287\u2013292|doi= 10.1007/s10989-009-9190-3|title=Multilayered Magnetic Nanoparticles as a Support in Solid-Phase Peptide Synthesis|first1=Katarina}}</ref>\n\nThis technology is potentially relevant to cellular labelling/cell separation, detoxification of biological fluids, tissue repair, drug delivery, magnetic resonance imaging, hyperthermia and magnetofection.<ref name=\"medicine\">{{cite journal|last=Gupta AK|author2=Gupta M|journal=Biomaterials|year=2005|volume=26|issue=18|pages=3995\u20134021|doi=10.1016/j.biomaterials.2004.10.012|title=Synthesis and surface engineering of iron oxide nanoparticles for biomedical applications|first1=Ajay Kumar|pmid=15626447}}</ref>\n\n'''Random versus site-directed enzyme immobilization'''\n\nEnzymes immobilized on magnetic nanoparticles (MNP) via random multipoint attachment, result in a heterogeneous protein population with reduced activity due to restriction of substrate access to the active site. Methods based on chemical modifications are now available where MNP can be linked to a protein molecule via a single specific amino acid (such as N- or C- termini), thus avoiding reduction in activity due the free access of the substrate to the active site. Moreover, site-directed immobilization also avoids modifying catalytic residues. One such common method involves using Alkyne-Azide Click chemistry as both groups are absent in proteins <ref>Shemsi, AM, Khanday F, Qureshi AH, Khalil A, Guerriero G, *Siddiqui KS (2019). Site-directed chemically-modified magnetic enzymes: fabrication, improvements, biotechnological applications and future prospects. Biotechnol. Adv. 37:357-381</ref>.\n\n===Catalyst support===\nMagnetic nanoparticles are of potential use as a [[catalyst]] or [[catalyst support]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A. Sch\u00e4tz |author2=O. Reiser |author3=W.J. Stark|journal=Chem. Eur. J.|year=2010|volume=16|issue=30|pages=8950\u201367|doi=10.1002/chem.200903462|pmid=20645330 |title=Nanoparticles as Semi-Heterogeneous Catalyst Supports|first1=Alexander}}</ref> <ref>{{cite journal|last=F. Panahi |author2=F. Bahrami |author3=A. Khalafi-nezhad|journal=Journal of Iranian Chemical Society|year=2017|volume=14|issue=10|pages=2211\u201320|doi=https://doi.org/10.1007/s13738-017-1157-2|title=Magnetic nanoparticles grafted l-carnosine dipeptide: remarkable catalytic activity in water at room temperature}}</ref>\nIn chemistry, a catalyst support is the material, usually a solid with a high surface area, to which a catalyst is affixed. The reactivity of heterogeneous catalysts occurs at the surface atoms. Consequently, great effort is made to maximize the surface area of a catalyst by distributing it over the support. The support may be inert or participate in the catalytic reactions. Typical supports include various kinds of carbon, alumina, and silica. Immobilizing the catalytic center on top of nanoparticles with a large [[surface to volume ratio]] addresses this problem. In the case of magnetic nanoparticles it adds the property of facile a separation<!-- Needs clarification.... -->. An early example involved a rhodium catalysis attached to magnetic nanoparticles .<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tae-Jong Yoon |author2=Woo Lee |author3=Yoon-Seuk Oh |author4=Jin-Kyu Lee|journal=New Journal of Chemistry|year=2003|volume=27|pages=227.229|doi=10.1039/B209391J|title=Magnetic nanoparticles as a catalyst vehicle for simple and easy recyclingElectronic supplementary information (ESI) available: XRD and FT-IR data, as well as the detailed experimental conditions for the catalytic hydroformylation reactions. See http://www.rsc.org/suppdata/nj/b2/b209391j/|first1=Tae-Jong|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Magnetic-chemistry-1.tif|frameless|center|430px|alt=Rhodium catalysis attached to magnetic nanoparticles]]\n\nIn another example, the stable [[Radical (chemistry)|radical]] [[TEMPO]] was attached to the [[graphene]]-coated cobalt nanoparticles via a [[diazonium]] reaction. The resulting catalyst was then used for the chemoselective oxidation of primary and secondary alcohols.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A. Sch\u00e4tz |author2=R. N. Grass |author3=W. J. Stark |author4=O. Reiser|journal=Chemistry: A European Journal|year=2008|volume=14|pages=8262\u20138266|doi= 10.1002/chem.200801001|pmid=18666291 |title=TEMPO Supported on Magnetic C/Co-Nanoparticles: A Highly Active and Recyclable Organocatalyst|first1=Alexander|issue=27}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Magnetic-chemistry-2.tif|frameless|center|550px|alt=TEMPO catalysis attached to magnetic nanoparticles]]\n\nThe catalytic reaction can be conducted in a [[continuous flow reactor]] instead of a [[batch reactor]] with no remains of the catalyst in the end product. Graphene coated cobalt nanoparticles have been used for that experiment since they exhibit a higher magnetization than [[Ferrite (magnet)|Ferrite]] nanoparticles, which is essential for a fast and clean separation via external magnetic field.<ref>{{cite journal|last=A. Sch\u00e4tz|author2=R. N. Grass |author3=Q. Kainz |author4=W. J. Stark |author5=O. Reiser |journal=Chemistry of Materials|year=2010|volume=22|pages=305\u2013310|doi=10.1021/cm9019099|title=Cu(II)\u2212Azabis(oxazoline) Complexes Immobilized on Magnetic Co/C Nanoparticles: Kinetic Resolution of 1,2-Diphenylethane-1,2-diol under Batch and Continuous-Flow Conditions|first1=Alexander|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Magnetic-chemistry-3.tif|frameless|center|550px|alt=Continuous flow catalysis]]\n\n=== Biomedical imaging ===\nThere are many applications for iron-oxide based nanoparticles in concert with [[magnetic resonance imaging]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Colombo | first1 = M | display-authors = etal   | year = 2012 | title = Biological Applications of Magnetic Nanoparticles | url = | journal = Chem Soc Rev | volume = 41 | issue = 11| pages = 4306\u201334 | doi=10.1039/c2cs15337h| pmid = 22481569 }}</ref> Magnetic CoPt nanoparticles are being used as an MRI contrast agent for transplanted [[neural stem cell]] detection.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Xiaoting Meng |author2=Hugh C. Seton |author3=Le T. Lu |author4=Ian A. Prior |author5=Nguyen T. K. Thanh |author6=Bing Song|journal=Nanoscale|year=2011|volume=3|pages=977\u2013984|doi=10.1039/C0NR00846J|bibcode = 2011Nanos...3..977M|title=Magnetic CoPt nanoparticles as MRI contrast agent for transplanted neural stem cells detection|first1=Xiaoting|issue=3|pmid=21293831 }}</ref>\n\n=== Cancer therapy ===\nIn magnetic fluid hyperthermia <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sharifi|first=Ibrahim|last2=Shokrollahi|first2=H.|last3=Amiri|first3=S.|date=2012-03-01|title=Ferrite-based magnetic nanofluids used in hyperthermia applications|journal=Journal of Magnetism and Magnetic Materials|volume=324|issue=6|pages=903\u2013915|doi=10.1016/j.jmmm.2011.10.017|issn=0304-8853|bibcode=2012JMMM..324..903S}}</ref>, nanoparticles of different types like Iron oxide, magnetite, maghemite or even gold are injected in tumor and then subjected under a high frequency magnetic field. These nanoparticles produce heat that typically increases tumor temperature to 40-46&nbsp;\u00b0C, which can kill cancer cells.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.3109/02656736.2014.988661 | pmid=25523967 | volume=31 | issue=1 | title=Cylindrical agar gel with fluid flow subjected to an alternating magnetic field during hyperthermia | journal=International Journal of Hyperthermia | pages=33\u201339| year=2014 | last1=Javidi | first1=Mehrdad | last2=Heydari | first2=Morteza | last3=Attar | first3=Mohammad Mahdi | last4=Haghpanahi | first4=Mohammad | last5=Karimi | first5=Alireza | last6=Navidbakhsh | first6=Mahdi | last7=Amanpour | first7=Saeid }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|pmc=4289522 | pmid=25599061 | volume=4 | issue=4 | title=Evaluation of the effects of injection velocity and different gel concentrations on nanoparticles in hyperthermia therapy | year=2014 | journal=J Biomed Phys Eng | pages=151\u201362 | last1 = Javidi | first1 = M | last2 = Heydari | first2 = M | last3 = Karimi | first3 = A | last4 = Haghpanahi | first4 = M | last5 = Navidbakhsh | first5 = M | last6 = Razmkon | first6 = A}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1142/S0219519415500888|title = Magnetic Fluid Hyperthermia in a Cylindrical Gel Contains Water Flow|journal = Journal of Mechanics in Medicine and Biology|volume = 15|issue = 5|pages = 1550088|year = 2015|last1 = Heydari|first1 = Morteza|last2 = Javidi|first2 = Mehrdad|last3 = Attar|first3 = Mohammad Mahdi|last4 = Karimi|first4 = Alireza|last5 = Navidbakhsh|first5 = Mahdi|last6 = Haghpanahi|first6 = Mohammad|last7 = Amanpour|first7 = Saeid}}</ref>\nAnother major potential of magnetic nanoparticles is the ability to combine heat (hyperthermia) and drug release for a cancer treatment. Numerous studies have shown particle constructs that can be loaded with a drug cargo and magnetic nanoparticles.<ref name = \"Estelrich 2015\">{{cite journal | last1 = Estelrich | first1 = Joan | display-authors = etal  | year = 2015 | title = Iron Oxide Nanoparticles for Magnetically-Guided and Magnetically-Responsive Drug Delivery | url = | journal = Int. J. Mol. Sci. | volume = 16 | issue = 12| pages = 8070\u20138101 | doi = 10.3390/ijms16048070 | pmid = 25867479 | pmc = 4425068 }}</ref> The most prevalent construct is the \"Magnetoliposome\", which is a [[liposome]] with magnetic nanoparticles typically embedded in the lipid bilayer. Under an alternating magnetic field, the magnetic nanoparticles are heated, and this heat permeabilizes the membrane. This causes release of the loaded drug. This treatment option has a lot of potential as the combination of hyperthermia and drug release is likely to treat tumors better than either option alone, but it is still under development.\n\n=== Information storage ===\n{{see also|MRAM}}\nA promising candidate for high-density storage is the face-centered tetragonal phase FePt alloy. Grain sizes can be as small as 3 nanometers. If it's possible to modify the MNPs at this small scale, the information density that can be achieved with this media could easily surpass 1 Terabyte per square inch.<ref name=\"nanoscienceworks.org\"/>.\n\n=== Genetic engineering ===\nMagnetic nanoparticles can be used for a variety of genetics applications. One application is the rapid isolation of DNA<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ernst|first=Constanze|last2=Bartel|first2=Alexander|last3=Elferink|first3=Johannes Wilhelmus|last4=Huhn|first4=Jennifer|last5=Eschbach|first5=Erik|last6=Sch\u00f6nfeld|first6=Kirsten|last7=Fe\u00dfler|first7=Andrea T.|last8=Oberheitmann|first8=Boris|last9=Schwarz|first9=Stefan|date=2019|title=Improved DNA extraction and purification with magnetic nanoparticles for the detection of methicillin-resistant Staphylococcus aureus|journal=Veterinary Microbiology|language=en|volume=230|pages=45\u201348|doi=10.1016/j.vetmic.2019.01.009|pmid=30827403}}</ref> and mRNA. In one application, the magnetic bead is attached to a poly T tail. When mixed with mRNA, the poly A tail of the mRNA will attach to the bead's poly T tail and the isolation takes place simply by placing a magnet on the side of the tube and pouring out the liquid. Magnetic beads have also been used in plasmid assembly. Rapid genetic circuit construction has been achieved by the sequential addition of genes onto a growing genetic chain, using nanobeads as an anchor. This method has been shown to be much faster than previous methods, taking less than an hour to create functional multi-gene constructs in vitro.<ref>{{cite book|chapter=Chapter 14. Advances in the Preparation and Biomedical Applications of Magnetic Colloids|author1=A Elaissari |author2=J Chatterjee |author3=M Hamoudeh |author4=H Fessi |title=Structure and Functional Properties of Colloidal Systems|editor=Roque Hidalgo-\u00c5lvarez|publisher=CRC Press|year= 2010|pages =315\u2013337|isbn=978-1-4200-8447-4|doi=10.1201/9781420084474-c14}}</ref>\n\n== Physical modeling ==\nThere are a variety of mathematical models to describe the dynamics of the rotations of magnetic nanoparticles.<ref>{{Cite book|last1=Reeves|first1=Daniel B.|title=Magnetic Characterization Techniques for Nanomaterials|date=2017|pages=121\u2013156|doi=10.1007/978-3-662-52780-1_4|publisher=Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg|language=en|isbn=978-3-662-52779-5|chapter=Nonlinear Nonequilibrium Simulations of Magnetic Nanoparticles}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reeves|first1=Daniel B.|last2=Weaver|first2=John B.|title=Approaches for Modeling Magnetic Nanoparticle Dynamics|journal=Critical Reviews in Biomedical Engineering|date=2014|volume=42|issue=1|doi=10.1615/CritRevBiomedEng.2014010845|pmid=25271360|pmc=4183932|language=English|issn=0278-940X|pages=85\u201393|arxiv=1505.02450}}</ref> Simple models include the Langevin function and the Stoner-Wohlfarth model which describe the magnetization of a nanoparticle at equilibrium. The Debye/Rosenszweig model can be used for low amplitude or high frequency oscillations of particles, which assumes linear response of the magnetization to an oscillating magnetic field.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carrey|first1=J.|last2=Mehdaoui|first2=B.|last3=Respaud|first3=M.|title=Simple models for dynamic hysteresis loop calculations of magnetic single-domain nanoparticles: Application to magnetic hyperthermia optimization|journal=Journal of Applied Physics|date=15 April 2011|volume=109|issue=8|pages=083921\u2013083921\u201317|doi=10.1063/1.3551582|issn=0021-8979|bibcode=2011JAP...109h3921C|url=https://hal.archives-ouvertes.fr/hal-01952248/file/JAP_Th%C3%A9orie_de_l%27hyperthermie.pdf|arxiv=1007.2009}}</ref> Non-equilibrium approaches include the Langevin equation formalism and the Fokker-Planck equation formalism, and these have been developed extensively to model applications such as magnetic nanoparticle hyperthermia, magnetic nanoparticle imaging (MPI),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Weizenecker|first1=J.|last2=Gleich|first2=B.|last3=Rahmer|first3=J.|last4=Dahnke|first4=H.|last5=Borgert|first5=J.|title=Three-dimensional real-time in vivo magnetic particle imaging|journal=Physics in Medicine and Biology|date=2009|volume=54|issue=5|pages=L1\u2013L10|doi=10.1088/0031-9155/54/5/L01|pmid=19204385|language=en|issn=0031-9155|bibcode=2009PMB....54L...1W|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/72744a865f7e6444c53e9b049025a2e97fd2fd75}}</ref> magnetic spectroscopy <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reeves|first1=Daniel B.|last2=Weaver|first2=John B.|title=Simulations of magnetic nanoparticle Brownian motion|journal=Journal of Applied Physics|date=15 December 2012|volume=112|issue=12|pages=124311|doi=10.1063/1.4770322|pmid=23319830|pmc=3537703|issn=0021-8979|bibcode=1998JChPh.109.4281T}}</ref> and biosensing <ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zhang|first1=Xiaojuan|last2=Reeves|first2=Daniel B.|last3=Perreard|first3=Irina M.|last4=Kett|first4=Warren C.|last5=Griswold|first5=Karl E.|last6=Gimi|first6=Barjor|last7=Weaver|first7=John B.|title=Molecular sensing with magnetic nanoparticles using magnetic spectroscopy of nanoparticle Brownian motion|journal=Biosensors and Bioelectronics|date=15 December 2013|volume=50|pages=441\u2013446|doi=10.1016/j.bios.2013.06.049|pmid=23896525|pmc=3844855}}</ref> etc.\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Iron oxide nanoparticles]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.fml.ethz.ch FML \u2013 Functional Materials Laboratory of the ETH Z\u00fcrich]\n* [http://nanos-sci.com/technology.html Properties and use of magnetic nanoparticle clusters (magnetic nanobeads)]\n* [http://news.cnet.com/8301-27083_3-10446292-247.html Magnetic nanoparticles target human cancer cells]\n* [http://www.physorg.com/news198570612.html Magnetic Nanoparticles Remove Ovarian Cancer Cells from the Abdominal Cavity]\n* Wiedwald, U. and Ziemann, P. (Ed.): [http://www.beilstein-journals.org/bjnano/browse/singleSeries.htm?sn=1 Properties and applications of magnetic nanoparticles], Thematic Series in the Open Access Beilstein Journal of Nanotechnology.\n* [https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0254058418306047 Effects of surfactant on the structural and magnetic properties of hydrothermally synthesized NiFe2O4 nanoparticles]\n== Bibliography ==\n* Catinon, M., Ayrault, S., Boudouma, O., Bordier, L., Agnello, G., Reynaud, S., & Tissut, M. (2014). ''Isolation of technogenic magnetic particles''. Science of the Total Environment, 475, 39-47 ([https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0048969713015647 abstract]).\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Magnetic Nanoparticles}}\n[[Category:Magnetism]]\n[[Category:Nanoparticles by physical property]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCatalyst support:Fixed cite & doi errors", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetic_nanoparticles"}
{"title_page": "Writer's Digest", "text_new": "{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Writer's Digest\n| image_file      = <!-- cover.jpg (omit the \"file: prefix -->\n| image_size      = <!-- 220px (the default if no size is stated) -->\n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = Ericka McIntyre,  January 2019\n| editor_title    = \n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| frequency       = 8 per year\n| circulation     = \n| category        = Articles\n| company         = [[Active Interest Media]]\n| publisher       = \n| firstdate       =  <!-- {{Start date|1920|December}} -->\n| country         = [[United States]]\n| based           = [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n| language        = English\n| website         =  {{URL|http://www.writersdigest.com}}\n| issn            = 0043-9525\n}}\n\n'''''Writer's Digest''''' is an American magazine aimed at beginning and established [[writer]]s.  It contains [[interview]]s, market listings, calls for [[manuscript]]s, and how-to articles.\n\nUntil 2019, it was owned by [[F+W|F+W Media]]. The magazine is published eight times per year.\n\nF+W Media, facing near-term liquidity issues with only about $2.5 million in cash available and $105.2 million in outstanding debt, filed on 10 Mar 19  for protection under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, citing in various documents a perfect storm of secular industry decline, poor investments, and even mismanagement.\nApparently their attempts to transition focus to online from print sales was poorly done.  Their users forum had not worked well for some time,  and the number of users had dropped way down from previous times.<ref>https://www.writersdigest.com/forums</ref>\n\nWD was bought by the Active Interest Media subsidiary of Cruz  Bay Publishing  and/or  PRH  (Penguin Random House) after bankruptcy of F+W, according to various sources. \nPenguin Random House is acquiring the book publishing assets of F+W Media, which include the Writer's Digest catalog.\nCruz bay got several magazines from F+W, including Writer's Digest, for $200,000, beating out enthusiast publisher Madavor Media.\n<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/03/12/writers-digest-popular-woodworking-publisher-fw-media-chapter-11-bankruptcy/3140354002/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.authorsguild.org/industry-advocacy/information-on-the-fw-writers-digest-bankruptcy/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/tonysilber/2019/03/11/fw-media-citing-debt-decline-and-mismanagement-files-for-bankruptcy-protection/#3938bbd54355</ref>\n<ref>https://the-digital-reader.com/2019/06/08/prh-buys-half-of-fw-media-at-auction-including-half-of-writers-digest/</ref>\n<ref>https://publishingperspectives.com/2019/06/penguin-random-house-wins-bid-to-buy-fw-medias-list/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.foliomag.com/fw-media-announces-winning-bidders-bankruptcy-auction/</ref>\n\n''Writer's Digest'' also [[sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]]s several in-house contests annually, including the ''Writer's Digest'' International Self-Published Book Awards and their Annual Writing Competition for [[short story|short stories]].\n\n''Writer's Digest'' partnered with book publisher BookBaby, the sister company of [[CD Baby]], in August 2014, to create a self-publishing division called Blue Ash Publishing, to provide instruction and education alongside book publishing and printing services. Blue Ash Publishing takes its name from the home office of the ''Writer\u2019s Digest'' editorial team located in [[Blue Ash, Ohio|Blue Ash]], Ohio.\n\n==History==\n[[File:TheFaulknerPortable.jpg|200px|right|thumb|A copy of the 1939 edition of [[Novel & Short Story Writer's Market|''Writer's Market'']], published by Writer's Digest Books rests next to [[William Faulkner|William Faulkner's]] [[Underwood Typewriter Company|Underwood]] Universal Portable typewriter in his office at his home, [[Rowan Oak]], which is now maintained by the [[University of Mississippi]] in [[Oxford, Mississippi|Oxford]] as a museum.]]\n\n''Writer's Digest'' was established in 1920 under the name ''Successful Writing'', first issue, December. It changed name to ''Writer's Digest'' with the March 1921 issue. By the late 1920s, it shifted emphasis more from literary-quality writing to the rapidly growing [[pulp magazine]] field, which offered the widest opportunities to freelance writers. An important feature from 1933 forward was the New York Market Letter, edited by [[Harriet Bradfield]], which gave timely updates on editor needs in the magazine field. As the pulp field collapsed in the 1950s, ''Writer's Digest'' shifted emphasis to famous writers and quality fiction.<ref>Locke, John; editor. ''Pulp Fictioneers: Adventures in the Storytelling Business'', Adventure House, 2004. {{ISBN|978-1-886937-83-3}}.</ref><ref>Sexton, Philip; editor. ''Legends of Literature: The Best Essays, Interviews and Articles from the Archives of Writer's Digest Magazine'', Writer's Digest Books, 2007. {{ISBN|1-58297-473-X}}.</ref><ref>Locke, John; editor. ''Pulpwood Days: Volume 1: Editors You Want to Know'', Off-Trail Publications, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-9786836-2-7}}.</ref>\n\nPaid circulation 63000 per 2017 media kit, down from 69000 in the 2016  media kit.\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Writer's Market]]''\n* ''[[Writer's Digest Short Story Contest]]''\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.writersdigest.com ''Writer's Digest'' magazine]\n* [http://www.writersonlineworkshops.com Writers Online Workshop, from ''Writer's Digest'' magazine]\n* [http://www.writersdigestconference.com/ehome/index.php?eventid=61986& ''Writer's Digest'' Writing Conference, from ''Writer's Digest'' magazine]\n* [http://www.blueashpublishing.com/ Blue Ash Publishing]\n\n{{F W Media}}\n\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:How-to]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Media in Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:American eight times annually magazines]]\n[[Category:Self-publishing]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox magazine\n| title           = Writer's Digest\n| image_file      = <!-- cover.jpg (omit the \"file: prefix -->\n| image_size      = <!-- 220px (the default if no size is stated) -->\n| image_alt       = \n| image_caption   = \n| editor          = Ericka McIntyre,  January 2019\n| editor_title    = \n| previous_editor = \n| staff_writer    = \n| frequency       = 8 per year\n| circulation     = \n| category        = Articles\n| company         = [[Active Interest Media]]\n| publisher       = \n| firstdate       =  <!-- {{Start date|1920|December}} -->\n| country         = [[United States]]\n| based           = [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n| language        = English\n| website         =  {{URL|http://www.writersdigest.com}}\n| issn            = 0043-9525\n}}\n\n'''''Writer's Digest''''' is an American magazine aimed at beginning and established [[writer]]s.  It contains [[interview]]s, market listings, calls for [[manuscript]]s, and how-to articles.\n\nUntil 2019, it was owned by [[F+W|F+W Media]]. The magazine is published eight times per year.\n\nF+W Media, facing near-term liquidity issues with only about $2.5 million in cash available and $105.2 million in outstanding debt, filed on 10 Mar 19  for protection under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, citing in various documents a perfect storm of secular industry decline, poor investments, and even mismanagement.\nApparently their attempts to transition focus to online from print sales was poorly done.  Their users forum had not worked well for some time,  and the number of users had dropped way down from previous times.<ref>https://www.writersdigest.com/forums</ref>\n\nWD was bought by the Active Interest Media subsidiary of Cruz  Bay Publishing  and/or  PRH  (Penguin Random House) after bankruptcy of F+W, according to various sources. \nPenguin Random House is acquiring the book publishing assets of F+W Media, which include the Writer's Digest catalog.\nCruz bay got several magazines from F+W, including Writer's Digest, for $200,000, beating out enthusiast publisher Madavor Media.\n<ref>https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2019/03/12/writers-digest-popular-woodworking-publisher-fw-media-chapter-11-bankruptcy/3140354002/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.authorsguild.org/industry-advocacy/information-on-the-fw-writers-digest-bankruptcy/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/tonysilber/2019/03/11/fw-media-citing-debt-decline-and-mismanagement-files-for-bankruptcy-protection/#3938bbd54355</ref>\n<ref>https://the-digital-reader.com/2019/06/08/prh-buys-half-of-fw-media-at-auction-including-half-of-writers-digest/</ref>\n<ref>https://publishingperspectives.com/2019/06/penguin-random-house-wins-bid-to-buy-fw-medias-list/</ref>\n<ref>https://www.foliomag.com/fw-media-announces-winning-bidders-bankruptcy-auction/</ref>\n\n''Writer's Digest'' also [[sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]]s several in-house contests annually, including the ''Writer's Digest'' International Self-Published Book Awards and their Annual Writing Competition for [[short story|short stories]].\n\n''Writer's Digest'' partnered with book publisher BookBaby, the sister company of [[CD Baby]], in August 2014, to create a self-publishing division called Blue Ash Publishing, to provide instruction and education alongside book publishing and printing services. Blue Ash Publishing takes its name from the home office of the ''Writer\u2019s Digest'' editorial team located in [[Blue Ash, Ohio|Blue Ash]], Ohio.\n\n==History==\n[[File:TheFaulknerPortable.jpg|200px|right|thumb|A copy of the 1939 edition of [[Novel & Short Story Writer's Market|''Writer's Market'']], published by Writer's Digest Books rests next to [[William Faulkner|William Faulkner's]] [[Underwood Typewriter Company|Underwood]] Universal Portable typewriter in his office at his home, [[Rowan Oak]], which is now maintained by the [[University of Mississippi]] in [[Oxford, Mississippi|Oxford]] as a museum.]]\n\n''Writer's Digest'' was established in 1920 under the name ''Successful Writing'', first issue, December. It changed name to ''Writer's Digest'' with the March 1921 issue. By the late 1920s, it shifted emphasis more from literary-quality writing to the rapidly growing [[pulp magazine]] field, which offered the widest opportunities to freelance writers. An important feature from 1933 forward was the New York Market Letter, edited by [[Harriet Bradfield]], which gave timely updates on editor needs in the magazine field. As the pulp field collapsed in the 1950s, ''Writer's Digest'' shifted emphasis to famous writers and quality fiction.<ref>Locke, John; editor. ''Pulp Fictioneers: Adventures in the Storytelling Business'', Adventure House, 2004. {{ISBN|978-1-886937-83-3}}.</ref><ref>Sexton, Philip; editor. ''Legends of Literature: The Best Essays, Interviews and Articles from the Archives of Writer's Digest Magazine'', Writer's Digest Books, 2007. {{ISBN|1-58297-473-X}}.</ref><ref>Locke, John; editor. ''Pulpwood Days: Volume 1: Editors You Want to Know'', Off-Trail Publications, 2007. {{ISBN|978-0-9786836-2-7}}.</ref>\n\nPaid circulation 63000 per 2017 media kit, down from 69000 in the 2016  media kit.\n\n== See also ==\n* ''[[Writer's Market]]''\n* ''[[Writer's Digest Short Story Contest]]''\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.writersdigest.com ''Writer's Digest'' magazine]\n* [http://www.writersonlineworkshops.com Writers Online Workshop, from ''Writer's Digest'' magazine]\n* [http://www.writersdigestconference.com/ehome/index.php?eventid=61986& ''Writer's Digest'' Writing Conference, from ''Writer's Digest'' magazine]\n* [http://www.blueashpublishing.com/ Blue Ash Publishing]\n\n{{F W Media}}\n\n[[Category:American literary magazines]]\n[[Category:How-to]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1920]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in Ohio]]\n[[Category:Media in Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Eight times annually magazines]]\n[[Category:Self-publishing]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Writer%27s_Digest"}
